# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university/21st-century-skills] During the latter decades of the 20th century and into the 21st century, society evolved through technology advancements at an accelerated pace, impacting economy and the workplace, which impacted the educational system preparing students for the workforce.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Beginning in the 1980s, government, educators, and major employers issued a series of reports identifying key skills and implementation strategies to steer students and workers towards meeting these changing societal and workplace demands.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Western economies transformed from industrial-based to service-based, with trades and vocations having smaller roles.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] However, specific hard skills and mastery of particular skill sets, with a focus on digital literacy, are in increasingly high demand.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] People skills that involve interaction, collaboration, and managing others are increasingly important.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Skills that enable flexibility and adaptability in different roles and fields, those that involve processing information and managing people more than manipulating equipment—in an office or a factory—are in greater demand.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] These are also referred to as "applied skills" or "soft skills", including personal, interpersonal, or learning-based skills, such as life skills (problem-solving behaviors), people skills, and social skills.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Many of these skills are also identified as key qualities of progressive education, a pedagogical movement that began in the late nineteenth century and continues in various forms to the present.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Since the early 1980s, a variety of governmental, academic, non-profit, and corporate entities have conducted considerable research to identify key personal and academic skills and competencies needed for the current and next generation.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Though identification and implementation of 21st century skills into education and workplaces began in the United States, it has spread to Canada, the United Kingdom, New Zealand, and through national and international organizations such as APEC and the OECD.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] In 1981, the US Secretary of Education created the National Commission on Excellence in Education to examine the quality of education in the United States.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The commission issued its report *A Nation at Risk: The Imperative for Educational Reform* in 1983.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Until the dawn of the 21st century, education systems across the world focused on preparing students to accumulate content and knowledge.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] As a result, schools focused on providing literacy and numeracy skills students, as these were perceived as necessary.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] However, developments in technology and telecommunication have made information and knowledge easily accessible.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Therefore, while skills such as literacy and numeracy remain relevant and necessary, they no longer sufficiently prepare students for 21st century workplace success.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] In response to technological, demographic and socio-economic changes, education systems began shifting toward curricula and instruction that integrated a range of skills involving, not only on cognition, but interdependencies of cognitive, social, and emotional characteristics.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Additional research has found that the top skills demanded by U.S.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Fortune 500 companies by the year 2000 had shifted from traditional reading, writing and arithmetic to teamwork, problem solving, and interpersonal skills.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] A 2006 Conference Board survey of some 400 employers revealed that the most important skills for new workforce entrants included oral and written communications and critical thinking/problem solving, ahead of basic knowledge and skills, such as the reading comprehension and mathematics.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Teachers and general citizens also played a critical role in its development along with the NGA and CCSSO by commenting during two public forums which helped shape the curriculum and standards.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] States also convened teams of teachers to assist and provide feedback looking towards the National Education Association (NEA) and many other education organizations to provide constructive feedback.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] As of December 2018, 45 states have entirely adopted the common core standards, one state has adopted half by only adopting the literacy section (Minnesota), and only four states remain who have not adopted into the common core standards of education (Alaska, Nebraska, Texas, and Virginia).
[src:university/21st-century-skills] This pedagogy involves creating, working with others, analyzing, and presenting and sharing both the learning experience and the learned knowledge or wisdom with peers, mentors, and teachers.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Additionally, these skills foster engagement; seeking, forging, and facilitating connections to knowledge, ideas, peers, instructors, and wider audiences; creating/producing; and presenting/publishing.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The classification or grouping has been undertaken to encourage and promote pedagogies that facilitate deeper learning through both traditional instruction as well as active learning, project-based learning, problem based learning, and others.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] A 2012 survey conducted by the American Management Association (AMA) identified three top skills necessary for their employees: critical thinking, communication and collaboration.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Below are some of the more readily identifiable lists of 21st century skills.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The Common Core Standards issued in 2010 intended to support the "application of knowledge through higher-order thinking skills." The initiative's stated goals promote the skills and concepts required for college and career readiness in multiple disciplines and life in the global economy.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Following the release of *A Nation at Risk*, the U.S.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Secretary of Labor appointed the **Secretary's Commission on Achieving Necessary Skills** (**SCANS**) to determine the skills needed for young people to succeed in the workplace fostering a high-performance economy.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] SCANS focused on a "learning a living" system.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] In 1991, an initial report was issued titled, *What Work Requires of Schools*.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The report concluded that a high-performance workplace requires workers who have key fundamental skills: basic skills and knowledge, thinking skills to apply that knowledge, personal skills to manage and perform; and five key workplace competencies.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Researchers at MIT, led by Henry Jenkins, Director of the Comparative Media Studies Program, in 2006 issued a white paper ("Confronting the Challenges of a Participatory Culture: Media Education for the 21st Century"), that examined digital media and learning.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] To address this Digital Divide, they recommended an effort be made to develop the cultural competencies and social skills required to participate fully in modern society instead of merely advocating for installing computers in each classroom.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] What they term participatory culture shifts this literacy from the individual level to a broader connection and involvement, with the premise that networking and collaboration develop social skills that are vital to new literacies.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] These in turn build on traditional foundation skills and knowledge taught in school: traditional literacy, research, technical, and critical analysis skills.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] A 2005 study (Lenhardt & Madden) found that more than one-half of all teens have created media content, and roughly one third of teens who use the Internet shared content they produced, indicating a high degree of involvement in participatory cultures.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Such digital literacies emphasize the intellectual activities of a person working with sophisticated information communications technology, not on proficiency with the tool.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] In 2003 the North Central Regional Educational Laboratory and the Metiri Group issued a report entitled "enGauge 21st Century Skills: Literacy in the Digital Age" based on two years of research.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The AAC&U conducted several studies and surveys of their members.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The ISTE Educational Technology Standards (formerly National Educational Technology Standards) are a set of standards published by the International Society for Technology in Education (ISTE) to leverage the use of technology in K-12 education.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] These are sometimes intermixed with information and communication technologies (ICT) skills.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] A person possessing these skills would be expected to perform these tasks for a particular set of information: access, manage, integrate, evaluate, create/publish/present.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The emphasis is on proficiency with digital tools.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] With the exponential expansion of personal access to Internet resources, including social media, information and content on the Internet has evolved from being created by website providers to communities of contributors and individuals.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The 21st century Internet centered on material created by a small number of people, Web 2.0 tools (e.g.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Wikipedia) foster online communication, collaboration, and creation of content by large numbers of people (individually or in groups) in online communities.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] In the report, they defined a set of 16 crucial proficiencies for education in the 21st century.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Those skills include six "foundational literacies", four "competencies" and six "character qualities" listed below.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] As a first step toward describing "21st century skills", the *National Research Council* identified three domains of competence: cognitive, interpersonal, and intrapersonal while recognizing that these domains intertwine in human development and learning.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] More specifically, these three domains represent distinct facets of human thinking, building on previous efforts to identify and organize dimensions of human behavior.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The committee produced the following cluster of 21st century skills in the above-mentioned three domains.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Additionally, CCR mapped the various competencies to the academic disciplines most conducive to their development.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] During its comprehensive research on AI’s present and future capabilities in education, CCR added an analysis of the more critical competencies in the age of AI, adding an “Emphasis” designation on specific facets of these competencies.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] For instance, since incremental creativity is reachable by AI, the human emphasis should be on imagination.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Lastly, CCR introduced the motivational drivers of personalized learning in an age of AI: Identity (& Belonging), Agency (& Growth mindset), and Purpose (& Passion).
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Multiple agencies and organizations issued guides and recommendation for implementation of 21st century skills supporting and encouraging change in learning environments and learning spaces.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Five separate educational areas impacted include standards, assessment, professional development, curriculum & instruction, and learning environments.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] The efforts to implement 21st century skills into learning environments and curricula supports the evolution of education systems from traditional practices or factory model school model into a variety of different organizational models.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Examples of hands-on learning and project-based learning are observable in programs and spaces such as STEM and makerspaces.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Collaborative learning environments fostered flexibility in furniture and classroom layout as well as differentiated spaces, such as small seminar rooms near classrooms.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Literacy with, and access to, digital technology also impacted the design of furniture and fixed components as students and teachers use tablets, interactive whiteboards and interactive projectors.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] Classroom sizes changed to accommodate a variety of furniture arrangements and groupings, as opposed to traditional configurations of desks in rows.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] In 2016, the Brookings Institution found that more than 100 countries embraced the concept of “21st century skills” in one terminology or another.
[src:university/21st-century-skills] However, further research by Brookings and CCR in 2018 showed that none of the major jurisdictions provided professional development to teachers, nor assessments of these competencies.
[src:university/8th-century] The **8th century** is the period from 701 (represented by the Roman numerals DCCI) through 800 (DCCC) in accordance with the Julian Calendar.
[src:university/8th-century] In the historiography of Europe the phrase **the long 8th century** is sometimes used to refer to the period of circa AD 660–820.
[src:university/8th-century] The coast of North Africa and the Iberian Peninsula quickly came under Islamic Arab domination.
[src:university/8th-century] The westward expansion of the Umayyad Empire was famously stopped at the siege of Constantinople by the Byzantine Empire and the Battle of Tours by the Franks.
[src:university/8th-century] The tide of Arab conquest came to an end in the middle of the 8th century.
[src:university/8th-century] In Europe, late in the century, the Vikings, seafaring peoples from Scandinavia, begin raiding the coasts of Europe and the Mediterranean, and go on to found several important kingdoms.
[src:university/8th-century] In Asia, the Pala Empire is founded in Bengal.
[src:university/8th-century] The Tang dynasty reaches its pinnacle under Chinese Emperor Xuanzong.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The first volume is dedicated to the emergence of the university in the Middle Ages and its development until around 1500.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Volume II describes and analyzes the university from the Reformation until the French Revolution (1500–1800), volume III the rise of the modern university until World War II (1800–1945) and the last volume the post-war period up to the present time.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The structure of the book follows a standardized systematic pattern throughout all volumes: the first part ("themes and patterns") introduces the reader to the university as an institution of its time.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The second part deals with the institutional "structures" of the university, the third with the "students", their education, activities and careers, and the fourth with individual fields of "learning" taught in the university.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Each section is divided into several chapters which were composed by specialists in the various subjects.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The main approach is holistic – the book aims less at covering the history of individual universities, but rather the character and historical trajectory of the institution as a whole.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] As of 2011, the series has been published in full in English and German, while the first volumes have appeared in Spanish and Portuguese and translations into Russian and Chinese are in preparation.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] In the English-language discourse, the book has been welcomed as an overhaul of Hastings Rashdall's long-time standard work *The Universities in Europe in the Middle Ages* and its 1936 revision by the medievalists F.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The book has received high praise from several reviewers.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Edward Grant regards the first part as "the best single volume on the history of medieval universities", noting its comprehensiveness, readability and authority produced by competent editorship and "outstanding contributors".
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Susan Rosa believes that this volume "sets a standard for competency in historical research", favourably mentioning the collaborative effort which produced little overlap between the various topics.
[src:university/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Matthew Kempshall calls the book "a product of an array of distinguished European scholars", but feels that it might have gone too far in idealizing the university as a supranational institution transcending state particularisms.
[src:university/abbey] An **abbey** is a type of monastery used by members of a religious order under the governance of an abbot or abbess.
[src:university/abbey] Abbeys provide a complex of buildings and land for religious activities, work, and housing of Christian or Buddhist monks and nuns.
[src:university/abbey] The concept of the abbey has developed over many centuries from the early monastic ways of religious men and women where they would live isolated from the lay community about them.
[src:university/abbey] Religious life in an abbey may be monastic.
[src:university/abbey] An abbey may be the home of an enclosed religious order or may be open to visitors.
[src:university/abbey] The layout of the church and associated buildings of an abbey often follows a set plan determined by the founding religious order.
[src:university/abbey] Abbeys are often self-sufficient while using any abundance of produce or skill to provide care to the poor and needy, refuge to the persecuted, or education to the young.
[src:university/abbey] Some abbeys offer accommodation to people who are seeking spiritual retreat.
[src:university/abbey] There are many famous abbeys across the Mediterranean Basin and Europe.
[src:university/abbey] The origins of abbeys are closely tied to the development of Christian monasticism, which began with individuals seeking spiritual fulfillment through asceticism and withdrawal from society.
[src:university/abbey] Similar monastic and ascetic traditions also exist in other religious traditions, including Hinduism, which has long supported organized forms of renunciation and monastic life.
[src:university/abbey] Early Christian monastic life often centered around hermits or ascetics who lived in solitude to dedicate themselves to prayer, fasting, and contemplation.
[src:university/abbey] These individuals typically resided in simple huts or caves, sometimes near a village or in remote areas.
[src:university/abbey] Over time, followers gathered around these ascetics, drawn by their perceived holiness and spiritual insight, eventually forming small religious communities.
[src:university/abbey] Comparable developments occurred in ancient India, where Hinduism has long supported traditions of renunciation.
[src:university/abbey] Hindu ascetics, known as *sannyasis*, often withdrew from worldly life to live in forest hermitages or remote monasteries known as *Mathas*.
[src:university/abbey] These institutions served not only as places of solitude and meditation but also as centers of religious learning and community life.
[src:university/abbey] In the Christian tradition, one of the earliest and most influential monastic figures was Anthony the Great, who around 312 AD retreated to the Thebaid desert in Egypt to escape persecution under Emperor Maximian.
[src:university/abbey] Anthony became renowned for his austere lifestyle and spiritual authority.
[src:university/abbey] His growing number of disciples eventually settled near him, building their own dwellings and forming one of the first organized monastic communities.
[src:university/abbey] According to the church historian August Neander, Anthony inadvertently laid the foundation for coenobitic monasticism—a communal way of life in which monks live together under a shared rule.
[src:university/abbey] This model became the basis for the development of Christian abbeys and monastic institutions throughout Europe and the broader Christian world.
[src:university/abbey] The emergence of communal religious life in both Christianity and Hinduism reflects a shared human inclination toward spiritual retreat and structured religious community, even though such institutions differ in form, theology, and purpose.
[src:university/abbey] At Tabennae on the Nile, in Upper Egypt, Saint Pachomius laid the foundations for the coenobitical life by arranging everything in an organized manner.
[src:university/abbey] He built several monasteries, each with about 1,600 separate cells laid out in lines.
[src:university/abbey] These cells formed an encampment where the monks slept and performed some of their manual tasks.
[src:university/abbey] There were nearby large halls such as the church, refectory, kitchen, infirmary, and guest house for the monk's common needs.
[src:university/abbey] An enclosure protecting all these buildings gave the settlement the appearance of a walled village.
[src:university/abbey] This layout, known as the *laurae* (lanes), became popular throughout Israel.
[src:university/abbey] As well as the "laurae", communities known as "caenobia" developed.
[src:university/abbey] These were monasteries where monks lived a common life together.
[src:university/abbey] The monks were not permitted to retire to the cells of a laurae before they had undergone a lengthy period of training.
[src:university/abbey] In time, this form of common life superseded that of the older laurae.
[src:university/abbey] In the late 300s AD, Palladius visited the Egyptian monasteries.
[src:university/abbey] He described three hundred members of the coenobium of Panopolis.
[src:university/abbey] There were fifteen tailors, seven smiths, four carpenters, twelve camel-drivers and fifteen tanners.
[src:university/abbey] These people were divided into subgroups, each with its own "oeconomus".
[src:university/abbey] A chief steward was at the head of the monastery.
[src:university/abbey] The produce of the monastery was brought to Alexandria for sale.
[src:university/abbey] The moneys raised were used to purchase stores for the monastery or were given away as charity.
[src:university/abbey] Twice in the year, the superiors of several coenobia met at the chief monastery, under the presidency of an "archimandrite" (the "chief of the fold" from the word, "miandra" (a sheepfold)) in order to make their reports.
[src:university/abbey] Chrysostom recorded the workings of a coenobia in the vicinity of Antioch in Syria.
[src:university/abbey] The monks lived in separate huts ("kalbbia") which formed a religious hamlet on the mountainside.
[src:university/abbey] They were subject to an abbot, and observed a common rule.
[src:university/abbey] The layout of the monastic coenobium was influenced by a number of factors.
[src:university/abbey] These included a need for defence, economy of space, and convenience of access.
[src:university/abbey] The layout of buildings became compact and orderly.
[src:university/abbey] Larger buildings were erected and defence was provided by strong outside walls.
[src:university/abbey] Within the walls, the buildings were arranged around one or more open courts surrounded by cloisters.
[src:university/abbey] The usual arrangement for monasteries of the Eastern world is exemplified in the plan of the convent of the Great Lavra at Mount Athos.
[src:university/abbey] With reference to the diagram, right, the convent of the Great Lavra is enclosed within a strong and lofty blank stone wall.
[src:university/abbey] The area within the wall is between three and four acres (12,000 and 16,000 m2).
[src:university/abbey] The longer side is about 500 feet (150 m) in length.
[src:university/abbey] There is only one entrance, which is located on the north side (A), defended by three iron doors.
[src:university/abbey] Near the entrance is a large tower (M), a constant feature in the monasteries of the Levant (Eastern Mediterranean area).
[src:university/abbey] The enceinte comprises two large open courts, surrounded with buildings connected with cloister galleries of wood or stone.
[src:university/abbey] The outer court, which is the larger by far, contains the granaries and storehouses (K), the kitchen (H) and other offices connected with the refectory (G).
[src:university/abbey] Immediately adjacent to the gateway is a two-storied guest-house, entered from a cloister (C).
[src:university/abbey] The inner court is surrounded by a cloister (EE) from which one enters the monks' cells (II).
[src:university/abbey] In the centre of this court stands the katholikon or conventual church, a square building with an apse of the cruciform domical Byzantine type, approached by a domed narthex.
[src:university/abbey] In front of the church stands a marble fountain (F), covered by a dome supported on columns.
[src:university/abbey] Opening from the western side of the cloister, but actually standing in the outer court, is the refectory (G), a large cruciform (cross shaped) building, about 100 feet (30 m) square, decorated within with frescoes of saints.
[src:university/abbey] At the upper end is a semicircular recess, similar to the triclinium of the Lateran Palace in Rome, in which is placed the seat of the hegumenos or abbot.
[src:university/abbey] This apartment is chiefly used as a meeting place, with the monks usually taking their meals in their separate cells.
[src:university/abbey] Monasticism in the West began with the activities of Benedict of Nursia (born 480 AD).
[src:university/abbey] Near Nursia, a town in Perugia, Italy, a first abbey was established at Monte Cassino (529 AD).
[src:university/abbey] Between 520 and 700 AD, monasteries were built which were spacious and splendid.
[src:university/abbey] All the city states of Italy hosted a Benedictine convent as did the cities of England, France and Spain.
[src:university/abbey] By 1415 AD, the time of the Council of Constance, 15,070 Benedictine monasteries had been established.
[src:university/abbey] The early Benedictine monasteries, including the first at Monte Cassino, were constructed on the plan of the Roman villa.
[src:university/abbey] The layout of the Roman villa was quite consistent throughout the Roman Empire and where possible, the monks reused available villas in sound repair.
[src:university/abbey] However, over time, changes to the common villa lay out occurred.
[src:university/abbey] The monks required buildings which suited their religious and day-to-day activities.
[src:university/abbey] No overriding specification was demanded of the monks but the similarity of their needs resulted in uniformity of design of abbeys across Europe.
[src:university/abbey] Eventually, the buildings of a Benedictine abbey were built in a uniform lay out, modified where necessary, to accommodate local circumstances.
[src:university/abbey] The plan of the Abbey of Saint Gall (719 AD) in what is now Switzerland indicates the general arrangement of a Benedictine monastery of its day.
[src:university/abbey] According to the architect and architectural historian Robert Willis (1800–1875), the Abbey's layout is that of a town of individual houses with streets running between them.
[src:university/abbey] The abbey was planned in compliance with the Benedictine rule that, if possible, a monastery should be self-contained.
[src:university/abbey] For instance, there was a mill, a bakehouse, stables, and cattle stalls.
[src:university/abbey] In all, there were thirty-three separate structures; mostly one level wooden buildings.
[src:university/abbey] The Abbey church occupied the centre of a quadrangular area, about 430 feet (130 m) square.
[src:university/abbey] On the eastern side of the north transept of the church was the "scriptorium" or writing-room, with a library above.
[src:university/abbey] The church and nearby buildings ranged about the cloister, a court about which there was a covered arcade which allowed sheltered movement between the buildings.
[src:university/abbey] The nave of the church was on the north boundary of the cloister.
[src:university/abbey] On the east side of the cloister, on the ground floor, was the "pisalis" or "calefactory".
[src:university/abbey] This was a common room, warmed by flues beneath the floor.
[src:university/abbey] Above the common room was the dormitory.
[src:university/abbey] The dormitory opened onto the cloister and also onto the south transept of the church.
[src:university/abbey] This enabled the monks to attend nocturnal services.
[src:university/abbey] A passage at the other end of the dormitory lead to the "necessarium" (latrines).
[src:university/abbey] On the south side of the cloister was the refectory.
[src:university/abbey] The kitchen, at the west end of the refectory was accessed via an anteroom and a long passage.
[src:university/abbey] Nearby were the bake house, brew house and the sleeping-rooms of the servants.
[src:university/abbey] The upper story of the refectory was called the "vestiarium" (a room where the ordinary clothes of the monks were stored).
[src:university/abbey] On the western side of the cloister was another two-story building with a cellar on the ground floor and the larder and store-room on the upper floor.
[src:university/abbey] Between this building and the church was a parlour for receiving visitors.
[src:university/abbey] One door of the parlour led to the cloisters and the other led to the outer part of the Abbey.
[src:university/abbey] Against the outer wall of the church was a school and headmaster's house.
[src:university/abbey] The school consisted of a large schoolroom divided in the middle by a screen or partition, and surrounded by fourteen little rooms, the "dwellings of the scholars".
[src:university/abbey] To the north of the church and to the right of the main entrance to the Abbey, was a residence for distinguished guests.
[src:university/abbey] To the left of the main entrance was a building to house poor travellers and pilgrims.
[src:university/abbey] There was also a building to receive visiting monks.
[src:university/abbey] These "hospitia" had a large common room or refectory surrounded by bed rooms.
[src:university/abbey] Each hospitium had its own brewhouse and bakehouse, and the building for more prestigious travellers had a kitchen and storeroom, with bedrooms for the guests' servants and stables for their horses.
[src:university/abbey] The monks of the Abbey lived in a house built against the north wall of the church.
[src:university/abbey] The whole of the southern and western areas of the Abbey were devoted to workshops, stables and farm-buildings including stables, ox-sheds, goatstables, piggeries, and sheep-folds, as well as the servants' and labourers' quarters.
[src:university/abbey] In the eastern part of the Abbey there was a group of buildings representing in layout, two complete miniature monasteries.
[src:university/abbey] That is, each had a covered cloister surrounded by the usual buildings such as the church, the refectory, the dormitory and so on.
[src:university/abbey] A detached building belonging to each contained a bathroom and a kitchen.
[src:university/abbey] One of the miniature complexes was called the "oblati".
[src:university/abbey] These were the buildings for the novices.
[src:university/abbey] The other complex was a hospital or infirmary for the care of sick monks.
[src:university/abbey] This infirmary complex included a physician's residence, a physic garden, a drug store, and a chamber for the critically ill.
[src:university/abbey] There was also a room for bloodletting and purging.
[src:university/abbey] The physic garden occupied the north east corner of the Abbey.
[src:university/abbey] In the southernmost area of the abbey was the workshop containing utilities for shoemakers, saddlers (or shoemakers, sellarii), cutlers and grinders, trencher-makers, tanners, curriers, fullers, smiths and goldsmiths.
[src:university/abbey] The tradesmen's living quarters were at the rear of the workshop.
[src:university/abbey] Here, there were also farm buildings, a large granary and threshing-floor, mills, and malthouse.
[src:university/abbey] At the south-east corner of the Abbey were hen and duck houses, a poultry-yard, and the dwelling of the keeper.
[src:university/abbey] Nearby was the kitchen garden which complemented the physic garden and a cemetery orchard.
[src:university/abbey] A priory was a smaller structure or entities which depended on the monastery.
[src:university/abbey] Some were small monasteries accommodating five or ten monks.
[src:university/abbey] Others were no more than a single building serving as residence or a farm offices.
[src:university/abbey] The outlying farming establishments belonging to the monastic foundations were known as "villae" or "granges".
[src:university/abbey] They were usually staffed by lay-brothers, sometimes under the supervision of a monk.
[src:university/abbey] Many of today's cathedrals in England were originally Benedictine monasteries.
[src:university/abbey] These included Canterbury, Chester, Durham, Ely, Gloucester, Norwich, Peterborough, Rochester, St Albans, Winchester, and Worcester.
[src:university/abbey] Shrewsbury Abbey in Shropshire was founded as a Benedictine monastery by the Normans in 1083.
[src:university/abbey] Westminster Abbey was founded in the tenth century by Saint Dunstan who established a community of Benedictine monks.
[src:university/abbey] The only traces of St Dunstan's monastery remaining are round arches and massive supporting columns of the undercroft and the Pyx Chamber.
[src:university/abbey] The cloister and buildings lie directly to the south of the church.
[src:university/abbey] Parallel to the nave, on the south side of the cloister, was a refectory, with a lavatory at the door.
[src:university/abbey] On the eastern side, there was a dormitory, raised on a vaulted substructure and communicating with the south transept and a chapter house (meeting room).
[src:university/abbey] A small cloister lay to the south-east of the large cloister.
[src:university/abbey] Beyond that was an infirmary with a table hall and a refectory for those who were able to leave their chambers.
[src:university/abbey] At the west entrance to the Abbey, there was a house and a small courtyard for the abbot.
[src:university/abbey] In 1055, St Mary's Abbey, York was built in England's north by the Order of Saint Benedict.
[src:university/abbey] The entrance to the abbey was through a strong gate on the northern side.
[src:university/abbey] This was for visitors arriving at the Abbey to make their devotions.
[src:university/abbey] Near the gate was the *hospitium* (guest hall).
[src:university/abbey] The buildings are completely ruined, but the walls of the nave and the cloisters are still visible on the grounds of the Yorkshire Museum.
[src:university/abbey] The Abbey was surrounded by fortified walls on three sides.
[src:university/abbey] The River Ouse bordered the fourth side.
[src:university/abbey] The stone walls remain as an excellent example of English abbey walls.
[src:university/abbey] The Abbey of Cluny was founded by William I, Duke of Aquitaine in 910 AD at Cluny, Saône-et-Loire, France.
[src:university/abbey] The Abbey was built in the Romanesque style.
[src:university/abbey] The Abbey was noted for its strict observance of the Rule of Saint Benedict.
[src:university/abbey] However, reforms resulted in many departures from this precedent.
[src:university/abbey] The Cluniac Reforms brought focus to the traditions of monastic life, encouraging art and the caring of the poor.
[src:university/abbey] The reforms quickly spread by the founding of new abbey complexes and by adoption of the reforms by existing abbeys.
[src:university/abbey] By the twelfth century, the Abbey of Cluny was the head of an order consisting of 314 monasteries.
[src:university/abbey] The church at the Abbey was commenced in 1089 AD by Hugh of Cluny, the sixth abbot.
[src:university/abbey] It was finished and consecrated by Pope Innocent II around 1132 AD.
[src:university/abbey] The church was regarded as one of the wonders of the Middle Ages.
[src:university/abbey] At 555 feet (169 m) in length, it was the largest church in Christendom until the completion of St Peter's Basilica in Rome.
[src:university/abbey] The church consisted of five naves, a narthex (ante-church) which was added in 1220 AD, and several towers.
[src:university/abbey] Together with the conventual buildings, it covered an area of twenty-five acres.
[src:university/abbey] In the Dechristianization of France during the French Revolution in 1790 AD, the Abbey church was bought by the town and almost entirely destroyed.
[src:university/abbey] As of 2025, however, fragments of the original Abbey still stand and archaeological excavations have intermittently been conducted over the past century, yielding a massively important and rich source of information.
[src:university/abbey] The first English house of the Cluniac order was built at Lewes, Sussex.
[src:university/abbey] It was founded by William de Warenne, 1st Earl of Surrey in about 1077 AD.
[src:university/abbey] All but one of the Cluniac houses in Britain were known as priories, symbolizing their subordination to the Abbot of Cluny.
[src:university/abbey] All the Cluniac houses in England and Scotland were French colonies, governed by French priors who travelled to the Abbey of Cluny to consult or be consulted (unless the abbot of Cluny chose to come to Britain, which happened rarely).
[src:university/abbey] In 1245 AD it was raised to the status of an abbey, answerable only to the Pope.
[src:university/abbey] The Augustinian (or "Austin") canons were an order of regular clergy within the hierarchy of the Catholic church.
[src:university/abbey] They held a position between monks and secular canons.
[src:university/abbey] They were known as "Black canons" because of the colour of their habits.
[src:university/abbey] In 1105 AD, the first house of the order was established at St Botolph's Priory, Colchester, Essex.
[src:university/abbey] The canons built very long naves to accommodate large congregations.
[src:university/abbey] Sometimes, as at Llanthony Priory and Christchurch, Dorset (Twynham), the choir was closed from the aisles.
[src:university/abbey] At other abbeys of the order, such as Bolton Abbey or Kirkham Priory, there were no aisles.
[src:university/abbey] The nave in the northern houses of the order often had only a north aisle (this is the case at Bolton, Brinkburn Priory and Lanercost Priory).
[src:university/abbey] The arrangement of the monastic buildings followed the ordinary plan.
[src:university/abbey] The prior's lodge was usually attached to the southwest angle of the nave.
[src:university/abbey] The Austin canons' house at Thornton, Lincolnshire had a large and magnificent gatehouse.
[src:university/abbey] The upper floors of the gatehouse formed the guest-house.
[src:university/abbey] The chapter-house was octagonal in shape.
[src:university/abbey] The Premonstratensian regular canons, or "White canons", were of an order founded in 1119 AD by Norbert of Xanten.
[src:university/abbey] The order was a reformed branch of the Augustinian canons.
[src:university/abbey] From a marshy area in the Forest of Coucy in the diocese of Laon, the order spread widely.
[src:university/abbey] Even in Norbert's lifetime, the order had built abbeys in Aleppo, Syria, and in the Kingdom of Jerusalem.
[src:university/abbey] Of the Abbey of Saint Samuel, Denys Pringle wrote, "The Premonstatensian abbey of Saint Samuel was a daughter house of Prémontré itself.
[src:university/abbey] Its abbot had the status of a suffragan of the patriarch of Jerusalem, with the right to a cross, but not to a mitre nor a ring." It long maintained its rigid austerity, though in later years the abbey grew wealthier, and its members indulged in more frequent luxuries.
[src:university/abbey] Just after 1140 AD, the Premonstratensians were brought to England.
[src:university/abbey] Their first settlement was at Newhouse Abbey, Lincolnshire, near the Humber tidal estuary.
[src:university/abbey] There were as many as thirty-five Premonstratensian abbeys in England.
[src:university/abbey] The head abbey in England was at Welbeck Abbey but the best preserved are Easby Abbey in Yorkshire, and Bayham Old Abbey in Kent.
[src:university/abbey] The layout of Easby Abbey is irregular due to its position on the edge of a steep river bank.
[src:university/abbey] The cloister is duly placed on the south side of the church, and the chief buildings occupy their usual positions around it.
[src:university/abbey] However, the cloister garth (quadrangle), as at Chichester, is not rectangular, and thus, all the surrounding buildings are positioned in an awkward fashion.
[src:university/abbey] The church follows the plan adopted by the Austin canons in their northern abbeys, and has only one aisle to the north of the nave, while the choir is long, narrow and without an aisle.
[src:university/abbey] Each transept has an aisle to the east, forming three chapels.
[src:university/abbey] The church at Bayham Old Abbey had no aisles in the nave or the choir.
[src:university/abbey] The latter terminated in a three-sided apse.
[src:university/abbey] The church is remarkable for its extreme narrowness in proportion to its length.
[src:university/abbey] While the building is 257 ft (78 m) long, it is not more than 25 ft (7.6 m) wide.
[src:university/abbey] Premonstratensian canons did not care to have congregations nor possessions.
[src:university/abbey] Therefore, they built their churches in the shape of a long room.
[src:university/abbey] The Cistercians, a Benedictine reform group, were established at Cîteaux in 1098 AD by Robert of Molesme, Abbot of Molesme, for the purpose of restoring, as far as possible, the literal observance of the Rule of Saint Benedict.
[src:university/abbey] La Ferté, Pontigny, Clairvaux, and Morimond were the first four abbeys to follow Cîteaux's example and others followed.
[src:university/abbey] The monks of Cîteaux created the well known vineyards of Clos-Vougeot and Romanée in Burgundy.
[src:university/abbey] The Cistercian principle of rigid self-abnegation carried over to the design of the order's churches and buildings.
[src:university/abbey] The defining architectural characteristic of the Cistercian abbeys was extreme simplicity and plainness.
[src:university/abbey] Only a single, central tower was permitted, and that was usually very low.
[src:university/abbey] Unnecessary pinnacles and turrets were prohibited.
[src:university/abbey] The windows were usually plain and undivided, and it was forbidden to decorate them with stained glass.
[src:university/abbey] The crosses were made of wood and the candlesticks of iron.
[src:university/abbey] The same principle governed the choice of site for Cistercian abbeys in that a most dismal site might be improved by the building of an abbey.
[src:university/abbey] The Cistercian monasteries were founded in deep, well-watered valleys, always standing at a stream's edge.
[src:university/abbey] The building might extend over the water as is the case at Fountains Abbey.
[src:university/abbey] These valleys, now rich and productive, had a very different appearance when the brethren first chose them as their place of retreat.
[src:university/abbey] Wide swamps, deep morasses, tangled thickets, and wild, impassable forests were their prevailing features.
[src:university/abbey] Clara Vallis of St Bernard, now the "bright valley" was originally, the "Valley of Wormwood".
[src:university/abbey] The plan of a Coptic Orthodox monastery, from Lenoir, shows a church of three aisles, with cellular apses, and two ranges of cells on either side of an oblong gallery.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Academic achievement is commonly measured through examinations or continuous assessments but there is no general agreement on how it is best evaluated or which aspects are most important—procedural knowledge such as skills or declarative knowledge such as facts.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Furthermore, there are inconclusive results over which individual factors successfully predict academic performance, elements such as test anxiety, environment, motivation, and emotions require consideration when developing models of school achievement.
[src:university/academic-achievement] In California, the achievement of schools is measured by the Academic Performance Index.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Individual differences in academic performance have been linked to differences in intelligence and personality.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Students with higher mental ability as demonstrated by IQ tests and those who are higher in conscientiousness (linked to effort and achievement motivation) tend to achieve highly in academic settings.
[src:university/academic-achievement] A recent meta-analysis suggested that mental curiosity (as measured by typical intellectual engagement) has an important influence on academic achievement in addition to intelligence and conscientiousness.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Children's semi-structured home learning environment transitions into a more structured learning environment when children start first grade.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Early academic achievement enhances later academic achievement.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Parent's academic socialization is a term describing the way parents influence students' academic achievement by shaping students' skills, behaviors and attitudes towards school.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Parents influence students through the environment and discourse parents have with their children.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Academic socialization can be influenced by parents' socio-economic status.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Highly educated parents tend to have more stimulating learning environments.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Further, recent research indicates that the relationship quality with parents will influence the development of academic self-efficacy among adolescent-aged children, which will in turn affect their academic performance.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Children's first few years of life are crucial for the development of language and social skills.
[src:university/academic-achievement] School preparedness in these areas helps students adjust to academic expectations.
[src:university/academic-achievement] The significance of social relationships in educational contexts is widely recognized, particularly in how these relationships influence learning and academic performance.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Notably, the characteristic of reciprocity within social relationships among children has been associated with enhanced academic performance.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Studies have shown that physical activity can increase neural activity in the brain, specifically increasing executive brain functions such as attention span and working memory; and improve academic performance in both elementary school children and college freshmen.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Non-cognitive factors or skills, are a set of "attitudes, behaviors, and strategies" that promotes academic and professional success, such as academic self-efficacy, self-control, motivation, expectancy and goal setting theories, emotional intelligence, and determination.
[src:university/academic-achievement] To create attention on factors other than those measured by cognitive test scores sociologists Bowles & Gintis coined the term in the 1970s.
[src:university/academic-achievement] The term serves as a distinction of cognitive factors, which are measured by teachers through tests and quizzes.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Non-cognitive skills are increasingly gaining popularity because they provide a better explanation for academic and professional outcomes.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Motivation is the reasoning behind an individual's actions.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Research has found that students with higher academic performance, motivation and persistence use intrinsic goals rather than extrinsic ones.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Furthermore, students who are motivated to improve upon their previous or upcoming performance tend to perform better academically than peers with lower motivation.
[src:university/academic-achievement] In other words, students with higher need for achievement have greater academic performance.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Self-control, in the academic setting, is related self-discipline, self-regulation, delay of gratification and impulse control.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Self-control is usually measured through self completed questionnaires.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Researchers often use the Self-Control Scale developed by Tangney, Baumeister, & Boone in 2004.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Through a longitudinal study of the marshmallow test, researchers found a relationship between the time spent waiting for the second marshmallow and higher academic achievement.
[src:university/academic-achievement] However, this finding only applied for participants who had the marshmallow in plain sight and were placed without any distraction tactics.
[src:university/academic-achievement] High locus of control, where an individual attributes success to personal decision making and positive behaviors such as discipline, is a ramification of self-control.
[src:university/academic-achievement] High locus of control has been found to have a positive predictive relationship with high collegiate GPA.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Family structure and involvement play a vital role in a child's education.
[src:university/academic-achievement] There are multiple types of family structures.
[src:university/academic-achievement] These family structures contribute in varying ways to a child's academic performance.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Factors of the family structure that can influence the child include pressure from parents, parents' marital status, and family socioeconomic status.
[src:university/academic-achievement] There are different types of socioeconomic stresses related to academics based on your family's income.
[src:university/academic-achievement] The more affluent children tend to face problems such as symptoms of anxiety, increased normalization of substance abuse, and symptoms of depression as early as middle school.
[src:university/academic-achievement] High-achieving students from this background tend to also face pressures from parents as well as society, which generally fails to account for their health and well-being.
[src:university/academic-achievement] These conditions make learning and academic success more difficult, especially in post-secondary schooling.
[src:university/academic-achievement] The more economically disadvantaged tend to struggle to attain academic success due to problems with money and the culture around it.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Though there is not one reason students perform worse on standardized measures of academic progress or success, such as the SAT and ACT, low-income students and districts perform worse on these tests.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Some challenge whether the tests and metrics that measure academic success are fair.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Organized extracurricular activities or cultural activities have yielded a positive relationship with high academic performance including increasing attendance rates, school engagement, GPA, postsecondary education, as well as a decrease in drop out rates and depression.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Additionally, positive developmental outcomes have been found in youth that engage in organized extracurricular activities.
[src:university/academic-achievement] High school athletics have been linked with strong academic performance, particularly among urban youth.
[src:university/academic-achievement] However, involvement in athletics has been linked to increased alcohol consumption and abuse for high school students along with increased truancy.
[src:university/academic-achievement] While research suggests that there is a positive link between academic performance and participation in extracurricular activities, the mechanism behind this relationship is not always clear.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Moreover, many unrelated factors influence the relationship between academic achievement and participation in extracurricular activities.
[src:university/academic-achievement] These variables include: civic engagement, identity development, positive social relationships and behaviors, and mental health.
[src:university/academic-achievement] In other research on youth, it was reported that positive social support and development, which can be acquired through organized after school activities is beneficial for achieving academic success.
[src:university/academic-achievement] In terms of academic performance there are a whole other group of variables to consider.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Some of these variables include: demographic and familial influences, individual characteristics, and program resources and content.
[src:university/academic-achievement] For example, socio-economic status has been found to plays a role in the number of students participating in extracurricular activities.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Furthermore, it is suggested that the peer relationships and support that develop in extracurricular activities often affect how individuals perform in school.
[src:university/academic-achievement] With all these variables to consider it is important to create a better understanding how academic achievement can be seen in both a negative and positive light.
[src:university/academic-achievement] In conclusion, most research suggests that extracurricular activities are positively correlated to academic achievement.
[src:university/academic-achievement] It has been mentioned that more research could be conducted to better understand the direction of this relationship.
[src:university/academic-achievement] Together this information can give us a better understand the exact aspects to consider when considering the impact that participation in extracurricular activities can have on academic achievement.
[src:university/academic-achievement] There are experiences analysed by research projects that show how the incorporation of Successful Educational Actions (SEAs) in schools with high absenteeism are contributing to the improvement of academic achievement.
[src:university/academic-bias] Conservative activists such as David Horowitz have argued that there is a bias against Christians and conservatives in academia.
[src:university/academic-bias] Barry Ames et al., John Lee and Henry Giroux have argued that these claims are based upon anecdotal evidence that would not reliably indicate systematic bias, and that the divide is due to self-selection due to conservatives simply being less likely to pursue an academic career.
[src:university/academic-bias] Russell Jacoby has argued that claims of academic bias have been used to push measures that infringe on academic freedom.
[src:university/academic-bias] One study of academic philosophers found that while half of respondents believed that ideological discrimination was wrong, a significant minority believed discrimination against individuals with opposing ideologies was justified.
[src:university/academic-bias] A 2017 paper argued that left-wing ideologies had taken over criminology in the 1960s and 1970s, observing a massive increase in research around fields such as radical, Marxist and feminist criminology.
[src:university/academic-bias] The authors also argue that even in the modern day, much of the writing in criminology remains primarily political in both origin and purpose.
[src:university/academic-bias] This was confirmed by the results of the study.
[src:university/academic-bias] Other researchers also argue that political bias manifests in scientific research, influencing how ideological groups are described, what measurements are used, the interpretation of results and which results are published.
[src:university/academic-bias] A 2018 study found bias amongst criminal law students, with students engaging in motivated reasoning favourable to their political in-group and demonstrating bias towards their political in-group.
[src:university/academic-bias] Mark Horowitz also argues that researchers' political views can bias their research.
[src:university/academic-bias] A 2005 paper argued that, controlling for student ability, there was no evidence of any disciplines being biased against conservative students in grading.
[src:university/academic-bias] In contrast, the researchers did find some disciplines, such as economics and business, where conservative students achieved higher grades than would be expected by student ability.
[src:university/academic-bias] Justin Tetrault argues that research into hate groups relied too much upon stereotypes rather than rigorous analysis, likely because said stereotypes appealed to researchers' own beliefs.
[src:university/academic-bias] It has been argued that apparent evidence of a "prejudice gap" between right-wingers and left-wingers—the idea that right-wingers are more prejudiced than left-wingers—was caused by researchers having not measured groups that left-wingers would be prejudiced towards.
[src:university/academic-bias] It has been suggested that this was because this was not regarded as prejudice or was not seen as worthy of investigation.
[src:university/academic-bias] Christine Reyna argues that ideological bias can affect how scales are constructed and interpreted in multiple ways.
[src:university/academic-bias] A 2019 study by the researchers measuring "actively open-minded thinking" noted that the researchers' original scale was biased against religious individuals due to test items, skewing correlations, and that the team had not realised this error for almost two decades, requiring a new scale.
[src:university/academic-bias] Zipp, have said that studies on the political orientations of professors are faulty, having focused on unrepresentative institutions and fields; when taken as a whole, they say that academia has become more moderate over time.
[src:university/academic-bias] The American Council of Trustees and Alumni, a conservative group, argues that course curriculums betray a progressive bias.
[src:university/academic-bias] However, John Lee argues that this research is not based on a probability sample and uses a research design that cannot rule out explanations other than political bias.
[src:university/academic-bias] Furthermore, research suggests little or no leftward movement among college students while they are in college.
[src:university/academic-bias] Academic bias has also been argued as a problem due to discrimination against conservative students.
[src:university/academic-bias] Research has indicated that conservative Christians may experience discrimination on colleges and universities, but these studies are anecdotal and rely on self-reported perceptions of discrimination.
[src:university/academic-bias] For example, the Hyers' study includes "Belief Conflicts" and "Interaction Difficulties" as discriminatory events.
[src:university/academic-bias] However, other work suggests that very few students experience discrimination based on political ideology.
[src:university/academic-bias] Phillip Gray argues that ideological bias in political science risks creating "blind spots", whereby certain ideas and assumptions are just accepted as normal and not challenged.
[src:university/academic-bias] Gray argues that this could mean that issues that concern the ideology of the dominant majority could receive a lot of focus, while issues that concern less prominent ideologies could be seen as less worthy of investigation and thus be consequently understudied.
[src:university/academic-bias] This risks resulting in a fairly ideologically homogenous field whereby certain "givens" are just accepted and thus not examined.
[src:university/academic-bias] In addition, Gray argues that this means that certain studies are not given adequate examination if they confirm the dominant group's ideological priors, even if the studies are flawed.
[src:university/academic-bias] Gray further argues that ideological bias in academia risks portraying other political groups not as another group of actors with their own beliefs but rather as a threat (too ignorant or prejudiced to know what is good) or menace (inherently inclined towards destructive acts and policies).
[src:university/academic-bias] Cofnas et al. argue that activism within social science can undermine trust in scientists.
[src:university/academic-bias] Brandt et al. argue that bias can limit what topics are researched and thus limit scientific knowledge as a whole.
[src:university/academic-bias] In addition, political bias in social science can risk creating a perception amongst the general public that the scientific field is producing politically biased findings and thus not worthy of receiving public funds.
[src:university/academic-bias] Surveys show that a college education tends to have a "regression to the mean" effect whereby both left-wing students and right-wing students moderate their views.
[src:university/academic-bias] Students also become more supportive of dissent and free speech during their education.
[src:university/academic-bias] An early audit study published in 1986 suggested that entrance into an American clinical psychology graduate program was negatively affected by whether the applicant was a fundamentalist Christian.
[src:university/academic-bias] One study examined the comments made by members of an American medical school admission committee towards 21 Christian applicants.
[src:university/academic-bias] It concluded that applicants were more likely to be criticised when responding to a question on abortion with an anti-abortion response.
[src:university/academic-bias] Reber assert that an implicit bias against theism limits possible insights in the field of psychology.
[src:university/academic-bias] Jeff Colgan argues that, amongst international relations data, there can be interpretive biases by researchers depending on their nationality, with bias towards the United States being common due to a large number of scholars being from the US.
[src:university/academic-bias] Sexism in academia refers to the academic bias and discrimination by a particular sex or gender in academic institutions, particularly universities, due to the ideologies, practices, and reinforcements that privilege one sex or gender over another.
[src:university/academic-bias] Sexism in academia is not limited to but primarily affects women who are denied the professional achievements awarded to men in their respective fields such as positions, tenure and awards.
[src:university/academic-bias] A vignette study found academic discrimination against men in Germany.
[src:university/academic-bias] Studies have also suggested that one reason for the unwillingness of conservatives to pursue academic careers may be because conservatives prefer higher paying jobs and are not as tolerant of controversial ideas as progressives.
[src:university/academic-bias] Empirical support for self-selection can be found in the work of Neil Gross.
[src:university/academic-bias] Gross conducted an audit study whereby he sent emails to directors of graduate study programs.
[src:university/academic-bias] He varied the emails so that some of them indicated the student supported the presidential candidacy of Senator John McCain, some of them supported the presidential candidacy of then Senator Barack Obama and some of them were politically neutral.
[src:university/academic-bias] He found that the directors of graduate study programs did not significantly vary in their treatment of the senders of the letters regardless of the implied political advocacy of that sender.
[src:university/academic-bias] His work suggests an absence of systematic discrimination against political conservatives.
[src:university/academic-bias] Academic bias can refer to several types of logocentrism or phonocentrism. or the belief that some sciences and disciplines rank higher than others.
[src:university/academic-bias] Asle Toje argues that while academic bias does not seem to make scholars dishonest, it does affect what questions are deemed worthy of research and what conclusions are deemed career-advancing.
[src:university/academic-bias] Toje also argues that the field of social science is filled with biased terminology that *a priori* discredits certain perspectives while lending credence to others.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] An **academic degree** is a qualification awarded to a student upon successful completion of a course of study in higher education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Academic degrees are commonly structured in levels, most often categorized as undergraduate and postgraduate degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The most common undergraduate qualification is the bachelor's degree, although some educational systems also offer lower-level degrees such as the associate degree or the foundation degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Postgraduate degrees include the engineer's degree, the master's degree, and the doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In the UK and countries whose educational systems are based on the British system, honours degrees are divided into classes: first, second (broken into upper second, or 2.1, and lower second, or 2.2) and third class.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doceo*, "I teach") first appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach (Latin: *licentia docendi*) at a medieval university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church when the term "doctor" referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* was originally reserved by the church which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed the access – now largely free of charge – of all able applicants, who were, however, still tested for aptitude by the ecclesiastic scholastic.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] This right remained a point of contention between the church authorities and the slowly emancipating universities, but was granted by the Pope to the University of Paris in 1231 where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] While the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*Baccalaureus*), it was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the Magister and doctorate, both of which now became the exclusive qualification for teaching.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In universities, doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Master of Arts" was seven years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] This was the same as the term of apprenticeship for other occupations.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Today the terms "master" (from the Latin *magister*, lit.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] 'teacher'), "Doctor", and "Professor" signify different levels of academic achievement, but in the Medieval university, they were equivalent terms.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The use of them in the degree name was a matter of custom at a university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Most universities conferred the Master of Arts, although the highest degree was often termed Master of Theology/Divinity or Doctor of Theology/Divinity, depending on the place.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The earliest doctoral degrees (theology – *Divinitatis* Doctor (D.D.), law – *Legum* Doctor (LL.D., later D.C.L.) and medicine – *Medicinæ* Doctor (M.D., D.M.)) reflected the historical separation of all higher university study into these three fields.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Over time, the D.D. has gradually become less common outside theology and is now mostly used for honorary degrees, with the title "Doctor of Theology" being used more often for earned degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Studies outside theology, law, and medicine were then called "philosophy", due to the Renaissance conviction that real knowledge could be derived from empirical observation.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The degree title of Doctor of Philosophy is a much later creation and was not introduced in England before 1900.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Studies in what once was called philosophy are now classified as sciences and humanities.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in medieval Islamic madrasas in the 9th century was the origin of the doctorate that later appeared in medieval European universities.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Alfred Guillaume, Syed Farid al-Attas and Devin J.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Stewart agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the university degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Stewart finds that the *ijazat al-ifta*, license to teach Islamic law and issue legal opinions, is most similar to the medieval European university degree in that it permits entry into certain professions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] A key difference was that the granting authority of the *ijaza* was an individual professor whereas the university degree was granted by a corporate entity.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The University of Bologna in Italy, regarded as the oldest university in Europe, was the first institution to confer the degree of Doctor in Civil Law in the late 12th century; it also conferred similar degrees in other subjects, including medicine.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The University of Paris used the term "master" for its graduates, a practice adopted by the English universities of Oxford and Cambridge, as well as the ancient Scottish universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The term "bachelor" comes from the Latin *baccalaureus*, a term previously used to describe a squire (i.e., apprentice) to a knight.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Further study and, in particular, successful participation in, and moderation of, disputations would earn one the Master of Arts degree, from the Latin magister, "master" (typically indicating a teacher), entitling one to teach these subjects.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Masters of Arts were eligible to enter study under the "higher faculties" of Law, Medicine or Theology and earn first a bachelor's and then master's or doctor's degree in these subjects.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Thus, a degree was only a step on the way to becoming a fully qualified master – hence the English word "graduate", which is based on the Latin *gradus* ("step").
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The naming of degrees eventually became linked to the subjects studied.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Scholars in the faculties of arts or grammar became known as "masters", but those in theology, medicine and law were known as "doctors".
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] As a study in the arts or grammar was a necessary prerequisite to study in subjects such as theology, medicine and law, the degree of doctor assumed a higher status than the master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] This led to the modern hierarchy in which the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), which in its present form as a degree based on research and dissertation is a development from 18th- and 19th-century German universities, is a more advanced degree than the Master of Arts (M.A.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The practice of using the term *doctor* for PhDs developed within German universities and spread across the academic world.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The French terminology is tied closely to the original meanings of the terms.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] "bachelor") is conferred upon French students who have completed their secondary education and allows the student to attend university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] When students graduate from university, they are awarded a *licence*, much as the medieval teaching guilds would have done, and they are qualified to teach in secondary schools or proceed to higher-level studies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Spain had a similar structure: the term *"Bachiller"* was used for those who finished the secondary or high-school level education, known as *"Bachillerato"*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The standard Spanish university 5-year degree was *"Licenciado"*, (although there were a few 3-year associate degrees called *"diplomaturas"*, from where the *"diplomados"* could move to study a related *licenciatura*).
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In the past, degrees have been directly issued by the authority of the monarch or by a bishop, rather than any educational institution.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In Great Britain, Lambeth degrees are still awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The Archbishop of Canterbury's right to grant degrees is derived from the Peter's Pence Act 1533, which empowered the Archbishop to grant dispensations previously granted by the Pope.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Among educational institutions, St David's College, Lampeter, was granted limited degree awarding powers by royal charter in the nineteenth century, despite not being a university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The University College of North Staffordshire was also granted degree awarding powers on its foundation in 1949, despite not becoming a university (as the University of Keele) until 1962.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Following the Education Reform Act 1988, many educational institutions other than universities have been granted degree-awarding powers, including higher education colleges and colleges of the University of London, many of which are now effectively universities in their own right.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, gaining an academic degree entitles the holder to assume distinctive academic dress particular to the awarding institution, identifying the status of the individual wearing them.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, degrees may only be awarded by institutions authorised to do so by the national or regional government.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Frequently, governments will also regulate the use of the word *university* in the names of businesses.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] This approach is followed, for example, by Australia, the United Kingdom and Israel.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The use of fake degrees by individuals, either obtained from a bogus institution or simply invented, is often covered by fraud laws.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the degree earned, degrees may be indicated by a pre-nominal title, post-nominal letters, a choice of either, or not indicated at all.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In countries influenced by the UK, post-nominal letters are the norm, with only doctorates granting a title, while titles are the norm in many northern European countries.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the purpose of the listing, only the highest degree, a selection of degrees, or all degrees might be listed.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The awarding institution may be shown and it might be specified if a degree was at honours level, particularly where the honours degree is a separate qualification from the ordinary bachelor's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] For member institutions of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, there is a standard list of abbreviations for university names given in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In practice, many variations are used and the Yearbook notes that the abbreviations used may not match those used by the universities concerned.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Other Latin abbreviations commonly used include 'Cantuar' for Lambeth degrees (awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury), 'Dunelm' for Durham University, 'Ebor' for the University of York and 'Exon' for the University of Exeter.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] The Ancient universities of Scotland and the University of London have abbreviations that are the same in English and Latin.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Confusion can result from universities sharing similar names, e.g. the University of York in the UK and York University in Canada or Newcastle University in the UK and the University of Newcastle in Australia.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] In this case, the convention is to include a country abbreviation with the university's name.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] For example, 'York (Can.)' and 'York (UK)' or 'Newc (UK)' and 'Newc (Aus.) are commonly used to denote degrees conferred by these universities where the potential for confusion exists, and institution names are given in this form in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Abbreviations used for degrees vary between countries and institutions, e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] MS indicates Master of Science in the US and places following American usage, but Master of Surgery in the UK and most Commonwealth countries, where the standard abbreviation for Master of Science is MSc.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Common abbreviations include BA and MA for Bachelor and Master of Arts, BS/BSc and MS/MSc for Bachelor and Master of Science, MD for Doctor of Medicine and PhD for Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:university/academic-degree-p01] Improvements in technology, the increasing use of the Internet worldwide, and the need for people to have flexible school schedules that enable them to work while attending school have led to a proliferation of online colleges that award associate's, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Bangladesh and India mostly follow the colonial era British system for the classification of degrees, however, Pakistan has recently switched to the US model of a two-year associate degree and a four-year bachelor's degree program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The arts, referring to the performing arts and literature, may confer a Bachelor of Arts (BA) and a Master of Arts (MA).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Management degrees are also classified under 'arts' but are nowadays considered a separate stream, with degrees of Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) and Master of Business Administration (MBA).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Science refers to the basic sciences and natural science (Biology, Physics, Chemistry, etc.); the corresponding degrees are Bachelor of Science (BSc) and Master of Science (MSc).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Information Technology degrees are conferred specially in the field of computer science, and include Bachelor of Science in Information Technology (B.Sc.IT.) and Master of Science in Information Technology (M.Sc.IT.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in India follows two nomenclatures, Bachelor of Engineering (B.Eng.) and Bachelor of Technology (B.Tech.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Both represent bachelor's degree in engineering.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In Pakistan, engineering degrees are Bachelor of Engineering (B.E.) and Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.S./B.Sc.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Both are the same in curriculum, duration and pattern, and differ only in nomenclature.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in Bangladesh is a Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.Sc.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Indonesia follows a higher education system that originated from the Dutch colonial period.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] However, over the years, Indonesia has transitioned from the Dutch degree classification system and developed its own academic distinctions by translating and adapting its degree structure.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia follow standardized regulations.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The duration of each program is specified by Regulation of the Minister of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia Number 3 of 2020 on National Standards of Higher Education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The regulation outlines the maximum duration and minimum credit requirements (Semester Credit Units or SKS) for each level of study without counting academic leave.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The degree structure follows a standardized pattern, where XX represents the specific field of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Since a semester consists of 14 or 15 weeks of coursework and 1 or 2 weeks of exams, one SKS translates to an average of 40 hours of study per semester.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Comparatively, one European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credit equals 28 hours of study, meaning that one Indonesian SKS is approximately equivalent to 1.5 ECTS.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Therefore, a bachelor's degree in Indonesia (minimum 144 SKS) is roughly equivalent to 216 ECTS, which surpasses the standard European requirement of 180 ECTS for a bachelor's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia grant academic titles, which are often used in formal and social settings, including on unofficial documents such as marriage invitations.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Before Indonesia adopted its modern degree classification, the country used a system copied from the Dutch colonial academic structure, which in Netherlands remained extant to 2002.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In this system, university students typically studied for five years before graduating.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] This structure was different from the modern four-year bachelor's (S1) degree, as it allowed graduates to proceed directly to a doctorate (S3) program without first obtaining a master's (S2) degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] This system included pre-nominal academic titles that have largely been phased out but are still recognized, for those who graduated before 1992.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Some of these titles are still in limited use today.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Doktorandus (Drs.) and Doktoranda (Dra.) originated from Latin, meaning "one who is to become a doctor." These titles indicated that the degree holder only needed to complete a dissertation to obtain a doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Until the 1960s, diplomas from Bandung Institute of Technology (ITB) explicitly stated that holders were entitled to pursue a doctorate upon defending a thesis.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] After the 1970s, ITB replaced Doktorandus and Insinyur (Engineer) titles with Sarjana (Bachelor) degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] However, these titles remained granted and used until 1992 in other universities or institutes.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] By aligning with Anglo education standards, Indonesia transitioned to the B.Sc. - M.Sc. - Ph.D. model, similar to the Bologna Process.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Unlike the previous system, where five-year graduates could proceed directly to a Ph.D., students must now complete an S1 (Bachelor's) and S2 (Master's) before pursuing S3 (Doctorate).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Despite this transition, many pre-1992 graduates retained the use of their original titles granted upon their graduation, making formats such as Prof.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Drs. [Name] common among senior academics and professionals.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Sri Lanka, like many other commonwealth countries, follows the British system, but with its own distinctions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Degrees are approved by the University Grants Commission.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Tunisia's educational grading system, ranging from elementary school to Ph.D. programs, operates on a scale of 0 to 20.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The minimum score for passing is set at 10 out of 20.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] This numerical system exclusively evaluates a student's academic accomplishments, serving as the determinant for admission into advanced programs.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] For instance, a student's grades obtained for their bachelor's degree are considered when they apply for a Master's program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Level 4 courses, which include the first year of a Bachelor's program or a Higher National Certificate (HNC), may allow students to enter directly into the second year of a Bachelor's program, provided that the course they completed is the same as the one they are applying for.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In South Africa, grades (also known as "marks") are presented as a percentage, with anything below 50% considered a failure.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Students who receive a failing grade may have the opportunity to rewrite the exam, depending on the criteria established by their institution.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Degrees in almost any field of study can be pursued at one of the institutions in the country, with certain institutions being known for excelling in specific fields.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Major fields of study across the country include Arts, Commerce, Engineering, Law, Medicine, Science, and Theology.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) has developed a credit-based system for degrees, with different levels of National Qualifications Framework (NQF) ratings corresponding to each degree level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] For example, an undergraduate degree in Science is rated at NQF level 6, while an additional year of study in that discipline would result in an NQF level 8 (honours degree) rating.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In Kenya, the first undergraduate degree is pursued after students have completed four years of secondary school education and attained at least a C+ (55–59%) on the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Students pursuing a degree in engineering, such as B.Sc.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Electrical and Electronics Engineering, are required to join programs that are accredited by the Engineers Board of Kenya and the Commission for University Education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The B.Sc. degree in engineering typically takes five years to complete.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] A degree in medicine or surgery may take six to seven years, while a degree in education or management takes around four years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] For students pursuing a master's degree, they must have completed an undergraduate degree and attained at least a second-class honours upper division (60–69%) or lower division plus at least two years of relevant experience.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Most master's degree programs take two years to complete.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In an engineering master's degree program, students are typically required to publish at least one scientific paper in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] To pursue a doctor of philosophy degree, students must have completed a relevant master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] They are required to carry out a supervised scientific study for a minimum of three years and publish at least two scientific first-author papers in peer-reviewed journals relevant to their area of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Currently, Kenya is implementing a Competency Based Curriculum (CBC) that follows a 2–6–3–3 education system to replace the existing 8–4–4 system which allows confirmation of undergraduate degrees upon successful completion.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] This system is gradually replacing the two-stage system previously used in some countries and is combined with other elements such as the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) and the use of Diploma Supplements to make comparisons between qualifications easier.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The European Higher Education Area (EHEA) was formally established in 2010 and, as of September 2016, has 50 members.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The implementation of the various elements of the EHEA varies between countries.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Twenty-four countries have fully implemented a national qualifications framework, and a further ten have a framework but have not yet certified it against the overarching framework.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In 38 countries, ECTS credits are used for all higher education programmes, and 31 countries have fully implemented diploma supplements.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Only 11 countries have included all the major points of the Lisbon Recognition Convention in national legislation.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Since 2008, the European Union has been developing the European Qualifications Framework (EQF).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] This is an eight-level framework designed to allow cross-referencing of the various national qualifications frameworks.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] While it is not specific to higher education, the top four levels (5–8) correspond to the short cycle, first cycle, second cycle, and third cycle of the EHEA.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The two-cycle degree system was phased out by 2010, with a few exceptions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] However, some of the established degree naming has been preserved, allowing universities to award the "Diplom-Ingenieur" (and for a while also the "Magister") to graduates of the new-style Master programmes.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] While higher education is regulated by the three communities of Belgium, all have common and comparable systems of degrees that were adapted to the Bologna structure during the 2000s.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The primary 3-cycle structure is called BMD (Bachelor-Master-Doctorate; French: *Bachelier-Master-Doctorat* or Dutch: *Bachelor-Master-Doctoraat*).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In the first cycle, the Bachelor's degree is issued after 180 ECTS (3 years, EQF level 6).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Other first cycle degrees include the one-year Advanced Bachelor's degree degree (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor') and the Brevet (in the French-speaking Community only) for short-cycle higher education programmes.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees are followed in the second cycle (EQF level 7) by Master's degrees that last two years, completing an extra 120 ECTS credits.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The master's degree can be followed by an Advanced Master's degree (French: *Master de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Master'; Dutch: *Master-na-master*, lit.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] 'Master-after-master') that lasts one year (60 ECTS).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic has implemented the Bologna process, and functionally has three degrees: Bachelor (3 years), Master (2 years after Bachelor) and Doctor (4 years after Master).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic also has voluntary academic titles called "small doctorates" (e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] RNDr. for natural sciences, PhDr. for philosophy, JUDr. for law etc.) which are achieved after passing an additional exam.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Medical students do not get bachelor's or master's degrees, but instead attend a six-year program and obligatory exam they achieve the title MUDr.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] (equivalent to MD degree in the United States of America), or MDDr. for dentists and MVDr. for veterinary physicians.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] They can also get a "big doctorate" (Ph.D.) after another three or four years of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and small doctorates in the form of letters (Bc., Mgr., Ing., ...) are listed before the person's name, and Doctor's degrees (Ph.D.) are listed after name (e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic previously had more degrees that were awarded.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Before the adoption of the Bologna Process, the lowest degree that would normally be studied at universities in Denmark was equivalent to a master's degree (*kandidatgrad*).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Officially, a bachelor's degree was always obtained after 3 years' university studies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Various medium-length (2–4 years) professional degrees have been adopted, so they now have status as professional bachelor's degrees of varying length.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] As opposed to academic bachelor's degrees, they are considered to be "applied" degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] A professional bachelor's degree is 180, 210, or 240 ECTS-points.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Historically, the Finnish higher education system is derived from the German system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The current system of higher education comprises two types of higher education institutions, the universities and the polytechnics, many of whom refer to themselves as universities of applied sciences (UAS).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] With the exception of a few fields, such as medicine and dentistry, the Finnish system of higher education degrees is in compliance with the Bologna process.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Universities award bachelor's degrees (*kandidaatti / kandidat*), Master's degrees (*maisteri / magister*) and doctoral degrees (*lisensiaatin tutkinto / licentiat examen* and *tohtorin tutkinto / doktorexamen*).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In most fields, the system of doctoral degrees is two-tier, the degree of licentiate is an independent academic degree but completing the degree of doctor does not require completion of a licentiate degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The polytechnics (universities of applied sciences) have the right to award bachelor's and master's degrees; the degree titles are distinct from the titles used for university degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In general, students who are admitted to bachelor studies at a university have the right to continue to studies at master level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] At polytechnics, the right to continue to master-level studies has to be applied for separately and there is also a work experience requirement.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The majority of master's degree holders have graduated from university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The degrees awarded by the universities and polytechnics are at par by law, but the content and orientation of studies is different.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] A master's degree obtained at a polytechnic gives the same academic right to continue studies at doctoral level as a master's degree obtained at a university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The French national education system makes a distinction between a *diplôme national* ("national degree") and *diplôme universitaire* ("university degree").
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The former, which are considered to have a higher status, are controlled by the state and issued by universities on behalf of the responsible ministry; the latter are controlled and granted by the universities themselves.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Additionally, private universities and schools may be recognised by the state with a *diplôme visé* ("recognised degree") and then, after five years of recognition, have their degrees validated by the state, the validation having to be renewed every six years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Historically, academic degrees were orientated towards research, and the vocational education system awarded only diplomas.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Since the implementation of the Bologna Process in France, the degree-granting system is being simplified: schools continue to grant their own diplomas, but the state's recognition in degree awarding is more important than before.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] However, in France there are diplomas that are not recognised as degrees, such as specific diplomas designed by colleges (*écoles supérieures*), like the *mastère spécialisé* (accredited by the *Conférence des Grandes Écoles* but not automatically by the French Government).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Since 2002, *grande école* diplomas have been able to award a university degree, such as the Sciences Po *Bachelor*, which is a state-accredited diploma that awards a bachelor's degree (*Licence* in French).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] The recognised degrees are in three levels, following the Qualifications Framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] These are the *licence* (first level), *master* (second level) and *doctorat* (third level).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] All licence degrees take 3 years (180 ECTS credits) and all master's degrees take 2 years (120 ECTS credits).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] There are also 5-year (300 ECTS credits) engineer's degrees, which are master's degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] In addition to the doctorate, which is always a research degree, the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur en médicine* and the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur vétérinaire* are third level qualifications and recognized as level 7 in EQF.
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] Traditionally in Germany, students studied for four to six years and then graduated with either a *Magister* degree (usually in subjects like humanities, linguistics or the arts) or a *Diplom* degree (typically in fields such as natural sciences, economics, or engineering).
[src:university/academic-degree-p02] These qualifications were usually the first and highest academic degrees students earned before a doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Both Magister and Diplom degrees from universities required a final thesis and are generally considered equivalent to a modern master’s degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, the Diplom awarded by a *Fachhochschule* (university of applied sciences) is usually considered comparable to a bachelor’s degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] A different type of qualification in Germany is the *Staatsexamen* (state examination).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This is not an academic degree but a government licensing examination required for certain professions, such as doctors, teachers, lawyers, judges, and pharmacists.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Students typically study at university for three to six years before taking the first Staatsexamen, depending on their field.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] After passing the first Staatsexamen, candidates in fields like law and teaching must complete a practical training period called the *Vorbereitungsdienst* (preparatory service), which usually lasts about two years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] They then take a second Staatsexamen, which tests their practical skills.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, students of law or pharmacy can choose to graduate with a master’s degree instead of taking the first Staatsexamen.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Since 1999, Germany has replaced its traditional university degrees with bachelor’s and master’s degrees as part of the Bologna process.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This reform aimed to make degrees more comparable internationally and to shorten the overall time students spend in higher education, as older programs often took five years or more to complete.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Today, students typically complete a bachelor’s degree followed by a master’s degree; the first usually taking 3 years, and the latter taking 18 months to 2 years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Some universities resisted the change, but by the end of 2007 all institutions were required to adopt the new system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Degree programs that lead to a Staatsexamen (state examination), such as those in law or medicine, were generally not converted to the bachelor’s/master’s system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In Germany, doctoral degrees are awarded with different titles depending on the subject area.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Examples include Doktor der Naturwissenschaften (Doctor of Natural Sciences), Doktor der Rechtswissenschaften (Doctor of Law), Doktor der Medizin (Doctor of Medicine), and Doktor der Philosophie (Doctor of Philosophy).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In German-speaking countries, it is common for people to list multiple doctorates and honorary titles, and sometimes even use them in formal address.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Students who have completed a Diplom, Magister, master’s degree, or Staatsexamen can usually continue on to a doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, particularly strong bachelor’s graduates may also be admitted directly to a doctoral program after passing an aptitude assessment set by the university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degrees (such as Dr. rer. nat. or Dr. phil.) are the highest academic qualifications in Germany and are typically based on independent research.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] (Doctor of Medicine): medical doctors often complete their doctoral thesis shortly after finishing their studies, and it may involve less independent research compared to doctorates in other fields.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some countries such as the United Kingdom, Germany does not have a system of “higher doctorates” (such as the Doctor of Science).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The Habilitation is an additional qualification beyond the doctorate, although it is not an academic degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It demonstrates the ability to carry out advanced research and teach at the university level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] To obtain a Habilitation, candidates usually write a second thesis (called a *Habilitationsschrift*) or submit a collection of significant research publications.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Once completed, the qualification is sometimes abbreviated as “habil.” after a person’s name.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Traditionally, the Habilitation was required to become a *Privatdozent* (a university lecturer qualified to teach independently) and to pursue a professorship.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Today, universities no longer require it, although it can still be an advantage in more traditional academic fields.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In Greece access to university is possible after national exams (Panhellenic Exams).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Ireland operates under a National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The school-leaving qualification attained by students is called the Leaving Certificate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It is considered as Level 4–5 in the framework.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This qualification is the traditional route of entry into third-level education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] There are also Level 5 qualifications in certain vocational subjects (e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Level 5 Certificate in Restaurant Operations) awarded by the Further Education and Training Awards Council (FETAC).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Advanced Certificates at Level 6 are also awarded by FETAC.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These are completed in institutes of technology or universities.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In Italy access to university is possible after gaining the *Diploma di Maturità* at 19 years of age, following 5 years of study in a specific high school focused on certain subjects (e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] After gaining the diploma one can enter university and enrol in any curriculum (e.g. physics, medicine, chemistry, engineering, architecture): all high school diplomas allow access to any university curriculum, although most universities have pre-admission tests.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In addition to academic degrees, many professional qualifications are tied to the QTI at the different levels.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The first level, tied to the first cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea* (bachelor's degree) in universities and the *Diploma accademico di primo livello* in AFAM institutions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The *laurea* is obtained after three years of study (180 ECTS credits) and confers the academic title of *dottore*; the older university qualifications at this level took two to three years, with the three-year courses conferring the title of *dottore*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The second level, tied to the second cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* of university institutions, and the *Diploma accademico di secondo livello* of AFAM institutions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* is mapped to this level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The *Laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* are obtained after two further years of study (120 ECTS credits) and give the academic title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* took four to six years but was accessed directly from school, with a possible reduction by one year for those with a related *diploma* and also granted the title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The third level, tied to the third cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *Dottorato di ricerca* from university institutions and the *Diploma accademico di formazione alla ricerca* from AFAM institutions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The old *Dottorato di ricerca* and *Diploma di specializzazione* are tied to this level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The *Dottorato di ricerca*, under both new and old systems, takes a minimum of three years after the *laurea magistralie/specialistica*, and gives the academic titles of *Dottore di Ricerca (Dott.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di specializzazione* took two to six years and gave the academic title of *Specialista*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di specializzazione*, which is offered in a few specific professions, takes two to six years and gives the title of *specialista*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di perfezionamento* is a university certificate, aimed at professional training or in specific fields of study, which usually takes one year; it is not allocated a level in the framework.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] AFAM institutions may offer the *Diploma di perfezionamento o Master* and *Diploma accademico di specializzazione*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These are one-year and two-year qualifications, respectively, and may be offered at the second cycle or third cycle level, distinguished by adding *(I)* or *(II)* after the qualification name.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Higher schools for language mediators offer the *Diploma di mediatore linguistico*, a first-cycle degree that takes three years (180 ECTS credits), and which gives access to the *laurea specialistica*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Specialisation institutes/schools in psychotherapy offer the *Diploma di specializzazione in psicoterapia*, a third-cycle qualification that takes at least four years and requires a *laurea magistrale/specialistica* in either psychology or medicine and surgery, along with professional registration.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the structure of academic studies was altered significantly in 1982 when the "Tweefasenstructuur" (Two Phase Structure) was introduced by the Dutch Minister of Education, Wim Deetman.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] With this structure an attempt was made to standardise all the different studies and to have them conform to similar timetables.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] An additional effect was that students would be forced to produce results within a preset time-frame or otherwise discontinue their studies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The two-phase structure has been adapted to a bachelor-master structure as a result of the Bologna process.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In order for a Dutch student to get access to a university education, the student must complete a six-year pre-university secondary education called *voorbereidend wetenschappelijk onderwijs* (VWO).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] There are other routes possible, but only if the educational level of the applicant is comparable to that at the end of the standard two levels is access to university education granted.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] For some studies, specific end levels or disciplines are required, e.g., graduating without having studied physics, biology and chemistry will make it impossible to study medicine.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] People 21 years old, or older, who do not have the required entrance diplomas, may opt for an entrance exam to be admitted to a higher-educational curriculum.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In this exam, they have to prove their command of disciplines considered necessary for pursuing such study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] After 1 September 2002, they would be thus admitted to a Bachelor's curriculum, not to a Master's curriculum.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] For some disciplines in the Netherlands, a governmentally determined limited access is in place (although under political review for abolishment, as of February 2011).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This limits the number of applicants to a specific course of study, thus trying to control the number of future graduates.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The disciplines most renowned for their numerus clausus are medicine and dentistry.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Every year a combination of the highest pre-university graduation grades and some additional conditions determine who can start such a numerus clausus course of study and who can not.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Almost all Dutch universities are government supported, with only a few privately owned universities in existence (i.e. one in business and all others in theology).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Leiden University is the oldest, founded in 1575.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] For medical students the "doctorandus" degree is not equivalent to the European Anglo Saxon postgraduate research degree in medicine, of MD (Medical Doctor).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Besides the title doctorandus, the graduates of the Curius curriculum may also bear the title *arts* (physician).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The doctorandus in medicine title is granted after four years (nominal time) of the Curius curriculum, while the title physician is granted after six years (nominal time) of that curriculum.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch physician title is equal to a MSc degree according to the Bologna process and can be compared with the MBBS in the UK degree system and the North American MD, but not the UK MD degree, which is a research degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] One-on-one equivalence or interchangeability of the Dutch medical title and MD is often suggested.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, officially the MD title is not known, nor legal to use, in the Netherlands.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The correct notation for a Dutch physician who completed his or her medical studies, but did not pursue a doctoral (PhD-like) study is "drs." (e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Jansen, arts*) and not "dr." in medicine, which is often used incorrectly.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, like in the United Kingdom, physicians holding these degrees are referred to as 'Doctor' by courtesy.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, there is the informal title *dokter* for physicians, but not *doctor* (dr.), unless they also earn such adegree by completing a PhD curriculum.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Furthermore, the *doctorandus* degree does not give a medical student the right to treat patients; for this a minimum of two years of additional study (internship) is required.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a Medical Board registration, Dutch physicians must work an additional two to six years in a field of expertise to become a registered medical specialist.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Dutch surgeons commonly are only granted access to surgical training and positions after obtaining a doctorate (PhD) successfully.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In recent years, the six-year (nominal time) old Curius curriculum (which offered the titles doctorandus and physician) has been replaced with a three-year (nominal time) Bachelor Curius+ followed by a three-year (nominal time) Master Curius+.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Those who had already begun their old-style Curius curriculum before that will still have to complete it as a six-year study (nominal time).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] A doctorandus in law uses the title *meester* (master, abbreviated as *mr.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Jansen*) instead of drs., and some courses of study, such as in technology and agriculture< grant the title *ingenieur* (engineer, noted as *ir.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These titles as equivalent to an LL.M (the title "mr.") and to a MSc (the title "ir.") and if gotten before 1 September 2002, from a recognized Dutch university, may be rendered as M (from Master) behind one's name, instead of using the typical Dutch honorifics before one's name.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, this M is hardly used in favor of the typical Dutch titles ("drs.", "ir.", "mr."), or MSc, MA or LLM.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Since 1 September 2002, Dutch universities offer specific BSc, BA or LLB studies followed by MSc, MA or LLM studies, thus integrating into the international scientific community, offering lectures, other classes, seminars or complete curricula in English instead of Dutch.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] According to their field of study, MSc graduates may use either ir. or drs. before their names; MA graduates may use drs. before their name; LLM graduates may use mr. before their names, but only if they received such degrees from recognized Dutch universities.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Not uncommonly, the Dutch "drs." abbreviation can cause much confusion in other countries, since it is perceived as a person who has a PhD in multiple disciplines.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the degree MPhil was not awarded after 2009 as the Universiteiten van Nederland refused to recognize the MPhils awarded by Leiden University.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] After successfully obtaining a "drs.", "ir." or "mr." degree, a student has the opportunity to follow a further, promotional course of study (informally called PhD) to eventually obtain a doctorate and subsequently the title "doctor".
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Promotion studies are ideally structured according to a preset time schedule of 4 to 6 years, during which the student has to be mentored by at least one professor.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The promotion study has to be concluded with at least a scientific thesis, which has to be defended to "a gathering of his/her peers", in practice the board of the faculty with guest professors from other faculties or universities added.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] More and more common—and, in some disciplines, even mandatory—is that the student write, and have accepted for publication by peer-reviewed journals, original scientific work.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The number of publications required is often debated and varies considerably between the various disciplines.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, in all disciplines the student is obligated to produce and publish a dissertation or thesis in book form.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] All current Dutch academic programs are offered under the Anglo-Saxon bachelor/master structure.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It takes three years to earn a bachelor's degree and another one or two years to earn a master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] There are three official academic bachelor titles (BA, BSc and LLB) and three official master titles (MA, MSc and LLM).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These academic titles are protected by the Dutch government.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a doctorate, Dutch doctors may bear either the title dr.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] (lower case) before, or the letter D following, their name, but not both simultaneously.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] There is no notation signifying the specific discipline in which the doctorate is obtained.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] As of 1 January 2021, the title 'PhD' and post-nominal degree 'PhD' can also be used, and these are also legally protected.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Stacking of titles, as seen in countries such as Germany (Prof.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Gruber), is highly uncommon in the Netherlands and not well received culturally.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Those who have multiple doctoral titles may use dr.mult. before their name, but this is seldom seen in practice.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The *honoris causa* doctors may use dr.h.c. before their name.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Combining different Dutch titles, especially in different disciplines, is allowed, however, (e.g. mr. dr.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The use of the combination ir. ing. is frequent, indicating one holds a HBO, vocational, or professional engineering degree "ing.", together with an academic engineering degree "ir.".
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] What is not allowed is, after obtaining a doctorate, using dr. drs.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] A combination of a Dutch title with an international title is not allowed, except for some limited number of international professional titles.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Thus, one should choose either one's classical Dutch title or use the shortcut provided by the law following one's name (since 1 September 2002 it is the other way around: those who hold Dutch degrees as MSc, LLM or MA may optionally use the old-style shortcuts before their names).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] "*Doctors*" (dr.) can proceed to teach at universities as "universitair docent" (UD – assistant professor).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] With time, experience and achievement, this can evolve to a position as "universitair hoofddocent" (UHD – associate professor).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Officially an UHD still works under the supervision of a "hoogleraar" (professor), the head of the department.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, this is not a given; it is also possible that a department is headed by a "plain" doctor, based on knowledge, achievement and expertise.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The position of "hoogleraar" is the highest possible scientific position at a university and equivalent to the US "full" professor.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch professor's title, noted as *prof.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Jansen* or *professor Jansen*, is connected to one's employment.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This means that, should the professor leave the university, he or she also loses the privilege to use the title of professor.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Retired professors are an exception and may continue to note the title in front of their name, or use the title emeritus professor (em. prof.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] People who switch to a non-university job lose their professorial title and are only allowed to use the "dr." abbreviation.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some other European countries, such as Germany, Dutch academic titles are used rarely outside academia, hold no value in everyday life, and typically are not listed on official documentation (e.g. passport, drivers license, (governmental) communication).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Dutch academic titles, however, are legally protected and can only be used by graduates from Dutch institutions of higher education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Illegal use is considered a misdemeanor and is subject to legal prosecution.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Holders of foreign degrees, therefore, need special permission before being able to use a recognised Dutch title, but they are free to use their own foreign title (untranslated).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In practice, the Public Department does not prosecute the illegal use of a protected title (the Netherlands applies prosecutorial discretion, so some known criminal uses are not prosecuted).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Prior to 1980, there were around 50 different degrees and corresponding educational programs within the Norwegian higher education system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Degrees had titles that included the gender based Latin term *candidatus/candidata*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The second part of the title usually consisted of a Latin word corresponding to the profession or training.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Magisterii) required 4 to 5 years, Cand.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Realium) required 6 years of study and a scientific thesis in a select set of scientific disciplines (realia).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Over the years these were replaced gradually with degrees that were more and more internationally comparable programs and corresponding titles.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These degrees were all retired in 2003 in favour of an international system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The reform of higher education in Norway, *Kvalitetsreformen* ("The Quality Reform"), was passed in the Norwegian Parliament, the Storting, in 2001 and carried out during the 2003/2004 academic year.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It introduced standard periods of study and the titles *master* and *bachelor (baccalaureus)*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The system differentiates between a free master's degree and a master's degree in technology.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The latter corresponds to the former *sivilingeniør* degree (not to be confused with a degree in civil engineering, which is but one of many degrees linked to the title *sivilingeniør*, which is still in use for new graduates who can choose to also use the old title).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] All pre-2001 doctoral degree titles were replaced with the title "Philosophical Doctor degree", written *philosophiæ doctor* (instead of the traditional *doctor philosophiæ*).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The title dr. philos. is a substantially higher degree than the PhD and is reserved for those who qualify for such a degree without participating in an organized doctoral degree program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In Poland, the system is similar to the German one.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Since 1992, Russian higher education has introduced a multilevel system, enabling higher education institutions to award and issue Bachelor of Science and Master of Science degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In Russia, Ukraine and some other former USSR republics educational degrees are awarded after finishing a college education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] There are several levels of education that one must choose in the 2nd and 3rd year of college, usually in the 3rd year of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] A specialist degree is awarded after 5 years of college (4 + 1).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] A Master's (Magister) degree is awarded after 6 years of college (4 + 2).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] But a Specialist degree can appear equivalent to Magister degree by reason of taking an equivalent amount of time.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Usually Specialist or Magister degrees incorporate the bachelor's degrees in them, but only the high-level degree is given on the final diploma.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Specialist and Magister degrees require taking final state exams and producing written work on practical application of studied skills or research thesis (usually 70–100 pages) and is roughly equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The first-level academic degree is called *Candidate of Sciences* ("Kandidat Nauk").
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Finally, there is a *Doctor of Sciences* ("Doktor Nauk") degree in Russia and some former USSR academic environments.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This degree is granted for contributions in a certain field (formally – who established new direction or new field in science).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It requires discovery of new phenomenon or development of new theory or essential development of new direction, etc.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] There is no equivalent of this "doctor of sciences" degree in the US academic system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It is roughly equivalent to Habilitation in Germany, France, Austria and some other European countries.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Candidate of Sciences* should be considered for recognition at the level of the first doctoral degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] According to *Guidelines for the recognition of Russian qualifications in the other countries*, in countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of the second doctoral degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In countries in which only one doctoral degree exists, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of this degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] LL.D. to *Candidate of Sciences of Legal Science*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Spain's higher-education legal framework includes official and accredited education, as well as non-official education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] In Spain, accreditation of official university study programmes is regulated by law and monitored by governmental agencies responsible for verifying their quality and suitability for official approval and accreditation.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Official professional study programmes lead to degree qualifications (*Títulos*) with full academic and professional rights.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Master's Degree (*Master Universitario*) – 60 to 120 ECTS Credits in 1–2 years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degree PhD (*Doctorado*) – in 3–4 years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Accredited bachelor's degrees and master's degrees qualifications will always be described as *Grado* and *Master Universitario*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These qualifications comply with the European Higher Education Area (EHEA) framework.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Officially approved and accredited university study programmes by law must implement this framework in order to attain and retain accreditation in Spain.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Not all EHEA-compliant study programmes in Spain are officially approved or accredited by government agencies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Some universities offer proprietary study programmes as alternatives for a variety of reasons: serving the continuing education market for individual self-advancement and also providing higher education to individuals who have failed to acquire bachelor's degree qualifications.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The main reason for offering these alternative studies, though, is the complex bureaucratic process required to receive the approval of specific titles, in particular when it refers to new studies or studies about matters that do not fit with the official studies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] For historical reasons, the academic system has been very much under the control of the state, and private universities are still regarded with as a threat to the state system.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These programmes fall within the category of "non officially approved and accredited" or *estudios no oficiales*, and they confer no academic or professional rights.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This means that they do not entitle the bearer to claim to have any specific academic or professional qualifications, as far as the Spanish authorities are concerned.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, there may be private agreements to recognize the titles.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Universities offering non-official study programmes are legally bound to clearly differentiate between officially-approved and non-officially-approved qualifications.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Non-accredited master's degrees will be described as just *Master*, without the accompanying *Universitario*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Certain non-officially approved and accredited study programmes may acquire a positive reputation.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] However, neither professional associations, government agencies, judiciary authorities, nor universities – other than the study programme provider – are obliged to recognize non-official qualifications in any way.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] All study programmes must be accredited by ANECA prior to their inclusion in the RUCT.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The RUCT records all officially approved universities and their bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and PhDs and each and every one of the officially approved and accredited study programmes.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Universities are assigned a specific number Code (*Código*) by the RUCT.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The same study programme may acquire different codes as it progresses through various stages of official approval by local and central governments.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Prospective students should check the RUCT Code awarded to the study programme of their interest at every stage of their enquiries concerning degrees in Spain.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] ANECA makes recommendations regarding procedures, staffing levels, quality of teaching, resources available to students and continuity or loss of accreditation.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry records all events in the life of an officially approved and accredited study programme or a university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry Search Facility may be the simplest and safest way to verify the status of all officially approved and accredited study programmes in Spain.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] It is also possible to track qualifications by using the search facility that several Autonomous Communities' own accreditation agencies offer.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The qualifications framework for higher education MECES is the reference framework adopted in Spain in order to structure degree levels.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Not all universities offer degrees named exactly the same, even if they have similar academic and professional effects.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Each university may present proposals for the study programme considered to meet professional and academic demand.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] The proposal will consist of a report linking the study programme being considered and the proposed qualification to be awarded.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] This report will be assessed by ANECA and sent for the Consejo de Universidades Españolas.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] If the *Consejo* agrees with ANECA's approval, it will be included in the RUCT and ANECA registries.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] All bachelor's and master's degrees accredited by ANECA bestow full academic and professional rights in accordance with new and previous laws.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Professional-practice law in Spain is currently under revision.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Before the Bologna Process, the academic degree of a Licentiate was reached after 4 or 5 years of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Depending on the official language of the university, it was called *Lizentiat* (German), *Licence* (French) or *licenza* (Italian) and, according to the Bologna reform, is today considered equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] A Licentiate with a predefined qualification gave access to the last stage of a further two or more years of studies (depending on the field) for a doctoral degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Apart from this, most universities offered a postgraduate diploma requiring up to two years of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] French-speaking universities called them *diplôme d'études approfondies* DEA or DESS, the Italian-speaking university *post laurea* and German-speaking universities mostly *Nachdiplomstudium* (NDS).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Today the federal legislation defines these postgraduate diplomas (60 ECTS credits) as Master of Advanced Studies (MAS) or Executive Master of Business Administration (EMBA) degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Universities may also offer the possibility to gain a diploma in advanced studies (DAS, less than 60 ECTS credits).
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] These degrees do not normally give access to a doctoral programme.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Turkish education system has been mostly compatible with the Bologna process before and immediately after adoption.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] New graduates of a bachelor's program from Turkish law faculties are required to enter a legal licensing examination from 2022 onwards, in order to use all the rights to the extent that has been granted by the related laws.
[src:university/academic-degree-p03] Such requirement does not exist for other degree holders.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] An academic degree is protected under UK law.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] All valid UK degrees are awarded by universities or other degree-awarding bodies whose powers to do so are recognised by the UK government; hence they are known as "recognised bodies".
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree in England, Northern Ireland and Wales is the bachelor's degree conferred with honours.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Usually this is a Bachelor of Arts (BA) or a Bachelor of Science (BSc) degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Other variants exist: for example, Bachelor of Education or Bachelor of Laws.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] It usually takes three years to read for a bachelor's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Candidates who have not achieved the standard for the award of honours may be admitted without honours to the "ordinary" bachelor's degree if they have met the required standard for this lesser qualification (also referred to as a "pass degree").
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Standard levels for each of these classes are 70%+ for a first, 60–69% for a 2:1, 50–59% for a 2:2, 40–49% for a 3rd and 30%+ for a pass degree, although this can vary by institution (e.g. the Open University).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree is a qualification, lower than bachelor's level, awarded following a two-year programme of study that is usually vocational in nature.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree can be awarded by a university or college of higher education that has been granted foundation-degree-awarding powers by the UK government.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] This degree is comparable to an associate degree in the United States.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The universities of Oxford and Cambridge award honorary Master of Arts (MA) degrees to graduates of their bachelor's programmes, following a specified period of time.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] This is comparable to the practice of the ancient universities in Scotland awarding an MA for a first degree and arguably reflects the rigorous standards expected of their graduates.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees such as Master of Arts or Master of Science are typically awarded to students who have undertaken at least a year of full-time postgraduate study, which may require study and involve an element of research.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Degrees such as Master of Philosophy (MPhil) or Master of Letters/Literature (MLitt) are likely to be awarded for postgraduate study involving original research.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] A student undertaking a master's would normally be expected to already hold a bachelor's degree in a relevant subject, hence the possibility of reaching the master's level in one year.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Some universities award a master's as a first degree following an integrated programme of study (an 'integrated master's degree').
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are usually designated by the subject, such as Master of Engineering for engineering, Master of Physics for physics, Master of Mathematics for mathematics and so on; it usually takes four years to read for them.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Graduation to these degrees is always with honours.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Master of Engineering in particular has now become the standard first degree in engineering at the top UK universities, replacing the older Bachelor of Engineering.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree is highly valued by those seeking to advance in business as managers and decision makers.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees or doctorates, such as the Doctor of Philosophy degree (PhD or DPhil) or Doctor of Education (EdD or DEd), are awarded following a programme of original research that contributes new knowledge within the context of the student's discipline.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees usually take three years full-time.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, in the UK it may only take seven years to progress from undergraduate to earning a doctorate – in some cases six, since having a master's is not always a precondition for embarking on a doctoral degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] This contrasts with nine years in the United States, reflecting differences in the educational systems.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Some doctorates, such as the Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy) qualification, confirm competence to practice in particular professions.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] UK post-secondary qualifications are defined at different levels, with levels 1–3 denoting further education and levels 4–8 denoting higher education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Within this structure, a foundation degree is at level 5; a bachelor's degree at level 6; a master's degree at level 7; and a doctoral degree at level 8.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Full information about the expectations for different types of UK degrees is published by the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] See also graduate certificate, graduate diploma, postgraduate certificate, postgraduate diploma and British degree abbreviations.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree for students studying arts or humanities in Scotland is either a Bachelor of Arts or a Master of Arts (the latter traditionally awarded by the Ancient Universities of Scotland for a first degree in an arts/humanities subject).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The standard undergraduate degree for natural and social science subjects is the Bachelor of Science.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Students can work towards a first degree at either ordinary or honours level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] A general or ordinary degree (BA/MA or BSc) takes three years to complete; an honours degree (BA/MA Hons or BSc Hons) takes four years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The ordinary degree need not be in a specific subject, but can involve study across a range of subjects within (and sometimes beyond) the relevant faculty, in which case it may also be called a general degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] If a third year or junior honours subject is included, the ordinary degree in that named discipline is awarded.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The honours degree involves two years of study at a sub-honours level in which a range of subjects within the relevant faculty are studied and then two years of study at honours level which is specialised in a single field (for example classics, history, chemistry, biology, etc.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Not all universities in Scotland adhere to this; in some, one studies in several subjects within a faculty for three years and can then specialise in two areas and attain a joint honours degree in fourth year.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] This also reflects the broader scope of the final years of Scottish secondary education, where traditionally five Highers are studied, compared to (typically) three English or Welsh A-Levels.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The Higher is a one-year qualification, as opposed to the two years of A-Levels, which accounts for Scottish honours degrees being a year longer than those in England.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Advanced Highers add an optional final year of secondary education, bringing students up to the level of their A-Level counterparts – students with strong A-Levels or Advanced Highers may be offered entry directly into the second year at Scottish universities.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Students who complete all the requirements for an honours degree, but who do not receive sufficient merit to be awarded third-class honours, may be awarded a *Special Degree* (ordinary degree – bachelor's level SCQF Level 9).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In most respects, the criteria for awarding qualifications at honours level and above are the same as in the rest of the UK (see above under England, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate qualifications are not designated Master of Arts, as in the rest of the UK, as this is an undergraduate degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate degrees in arts and humanities subjects are usually designated Master of Letters (M.Litt.) or, in natural and social sciences, Master of Science (M.Sc.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Non-doctoral postgraduate research degrees are usually designated Master of Philosophy (M.Phil.) or Master of Research (M.Res.).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The postgraduate teaching qualification is the Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, education is the responsibility of the provinces and territories, rather than the federal government.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] However, all of Canada follows the three-level bachelor's-master's-doctorate system common to the Anglophone world, with a few variations.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] A common framework for degrees was agreed between the provinces and territories in 2007.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor's degrees take normally three to four years, more commonly three years in Quebec (where they follow on from college courses rather than directly from secondary education).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Outside Quebec, three-year bachelor's degrees are normally ordinary degrees, while four-year bachelor's degrees are honours degrees; an honours degree is normally needed for further study at the master's level.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees take one to three years (in Quebec they normally take one and a half to two years).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates take a minimum of three years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Alone among Canadian provinces and territories, British Columbia offers two-year associate degrees, allowing credit to be transferred into a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, first professional degrees such as DDS, MD, PharmD and LLB or JD are considered bachelor's level qualifications, despite their often being named as if they were doctorates.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In the province of Quebec, the majority of students must attend college prior to entering university.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Upon completion of a two-year pre-university program, such as in sciences or humanities, or a three-year technical program, such as nursing or computer science, college graduates obtain a *college diploma*, which is a prerequisite for access to university-level studies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Although these college programs are typical, they are not offered in every institution in the province.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Moreover, while a few other pre-university programs with various concentrations exist, many other technical/career programs are available, depending on the college of choice.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] For example, Dawson College in Montreal has nearly sixty different programs leading to a college diploma.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Special programs, such as physical rehabilitation therapy, are offered in some colleges as well.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] A similar option is offered for college nursing graduates as they can pursue their studies in university to obtain a Bachelor of Nursing in two years (rather than the usual three or four years, depending on whether the student has completed a college diploma in Quebec).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Education in Mexico follows a three-degree system similar to that of Canada and the US.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The pre-university academic level is the *bachillerato* (also called *preparatoria*), similar to high school.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] They can also get the degree of "ingenieria" or "medico" as an engineer or MD, respectively.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] After receiving the *licenciatura*, students may take extra courses called *diplomados* (similar to a certification but issued by a university).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These courses last 4–12 months and are a means to further study without continuing to the next degree level, and are usually to demonstrate that students are staying up-to-date in their fields.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Most students stay at this level, but some choose to continue to the *maestría*, equivalent to the master's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Study at the *maestría* level takes 1–3 years and mandates completion of a thesis.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Post-graduate students in Mexico typically enter a master's program after a few years in the workforce and often continue working while studying.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, students who have completed the *maestria* may continue on to the *doctorado* or the doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral study typically lasts 3–4 years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In recent years this schemes has become flexible such that in some PhD programmes, students are accepted before, or not completing, the course of study for a master's.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In the United States, since the late 19th century, the threefold degree system of bachelor's, master's, and doctorate has been in place but has evolved into a slightly different pattern from the European equivalent.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Department of Education now classifies degrees in six categories: associate degrees, bachelor's degrees, first professional degrees, master's degrees, intermediate graduate qualifications and research doctorates.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The standard academic progression remains bachelor's—master's—(research) doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] This timetable is only approximate, however, as students in accelerated programs can sometimes earn a bachelor's degree in three years or, on the other hand, a particular dissertation project might take four or more years to complete.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In addition, a graduate may wait an indeterminate time between degrees before candidacy in the next level or even an additional degree at a level already completed.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, there is no time limit on the accumulation of academic degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] By far the most common research doctorate is the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), comprising 98.1% of research doctorates in 2014.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The Doctor of Education (Ed.D.) made up 1.1% (not including Ed.D.s classified as professional degrees rather than research doctorates) and all other research doctorates were less than 1% in total.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Some schools, mostly junior colleges and community colleges and some four-year schools, offer an associate degree that takes two full years of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These may be in professional or academic fields, and the most common awards are the Associate of Arts (A.A.) and Associate of Science (A.S.) degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Articulation agreements may allow credit earned on an associate degree to be counted toward the completion of a bachelor's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The "first professional degree" is a graduate-level degree program designed to prepare graduates for professional practice in various fields other than academic scholarship and research.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees require a minimum of two years of college-level education prior to entering the program and a minimum of six years of total college-level education (including that undertaken prior to entry) to complete the program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Most professional degree programs require a prior bachelor's degree for admission and many require seven or eight years of total study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] M.D., J.D. or D.O. are named as doctorates but should not be confused with research doctorates such as the Ph.D.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees should also not be confused with professional master's degrees such as the M.Arch. and M.B.A., which are classified as master's degrees, or with intermediate graduate qualifications that also bear the title of doctor, such as D.Min. or D.Psy.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Intermediate graduate qualifications lie between the master's level and doctorate.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] They include awards such as the Certificate of Advanced Study, Graduate Diplomas, Professional Engineer status, and Professional Diplomas, as well as specialist degrees such as Education Specialist, Doctor of Ministry, Doctor of Psychology and the Licentiate in Sacred Theology.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In 21 US jurisdictions, religious institutions can be authorized to grant religious-exempt (rel. exmpt., rel. expt., etc.) degrees without accreditation or government oversight.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Such degrees are used primarily to attain church-related employment.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, more men than women attended and earned degrees at the world's universities.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] A milestone was reached in the United States, according to the 2010 census, as women surpassed men in attaining master's degrees, for the first time.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The U.S. census reports that 10.5 million men have master's degrees or higher, compared with 10.6 million women.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The first year that women surpassed men in earning bachelor's degrees was 1996.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Students, the media, and the general public have shown much concern over the value of getting a higher degree in the US ever since the Great Recession of 2007.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Media coverage of the rising costs of higher education and increased student debt have also affected the public's perceptions of whether higher degrees are still worthwhile.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Statistics citing that college graduates make around $1 million more in their lifetimes than those who did not attend college and live longer, healthier lives work in favor of those who argue the continued value of higher degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Studies like the 2011 Learning Gains study by Arum and Roksa, on the other hand, reported that only 55% of students had any learning gains during their first two years of college, which favors the argument that investing in higher education may not still be worth it.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) covers 10 levels, of which levels 6–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Also included within the higher education system are: diplomas at level 5 (first year of a degree course); advanced diplomas, at level 6 (associate degree level); and graduate certificates and graduate diplomas, both of which are at level 8 (honours degree level).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In Australia, most degrees are issued ungraded, with bachelor's degrees with honours being the exception.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates in Australia may be research doctorates (normally titled PhDs), professional doctorates (normally titled to refer to the field of practice, e.g.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctor of Engineering) or higher doctorates (also normally titled to refer to the field of practice).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Extended master's degrees are also allowed to have the word 'doctor' in their title if they are in certain fields, but they are not doctoral degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Like Australia, New Zealand has a 10-level qualifications framework (the New Zealand Qualifications Framework – NZQF) and a referencing exercise has found a one-to-one correspondence between the levels of the two frameworks.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] However, the names given to qualifications at different levels are not the same and New Zealand does not have associate degrees, thus only levels 7–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These are the bachelor's degree (level 7), bachelor honours degree (level 8), master's degree (level 9) and the doctoral degree (level 10).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In addition to these, the NZQF has certificates across levels 1–6, diplomas at levels 5 and 6, graduate certificates and graduate diplomas at level 7 (bachelor's), and postgraduate certificates and postgraduate diplomas at level 8 (honours).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Another referencing exercise, comparing the NZQF to the 10-level Irish National Framework for Qualifications, found that degrees were comparable but that further work was needed to improve compatibility at the sub-degree levels (1–6).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Non-degree qualifications at levels 7–9 were not included in the study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In New Zealand, master's degrees may be awarded with classified honours (1st, 2:1, 2:2, 3rd) or with distinction or merit.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate students in Brazilian universities graduate either with a bachelor's degree, a licentiate degree or a technologist degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor degrees in Brazil normally take four or five years of full-time study to complete, with the exception of the human medicine course, which requires six years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Licentiate degrees normally take four-years, and are for students who want to qualify as school teachers.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] *Licenciatura* courses exist mostly in mathematics, humanities and natural sciences.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The technologist degree is available in technology-related fields and can be normally obtained in three years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are for entry into industry.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Admission as an undergraduate student to most top public or private universities in Brazil requires that the applicant pass a competitive entrance examination known as the Vestibular.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Contrary to what happens in the United States, candidates must declare their intended university major when they register for the Vestibular.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Although it is theoretically possible to switch majors afterwards (in a process known within the universities as *transferência interna*), that is actually quite rare in Brazil.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate curricula tend to be more rigid than in the United States and there is little room to take classes outside one's major.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Individuals who hold either a bachelor's degree, licentiate or technologist are eligible for admission into graduate courses leading to advanced master's or doctor's degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Criteria for admission into master's and doctor's programs vary in Brazil.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Some universities require that candidates take entrance exams; others make admission decisions based solely on undergraduate transcripts, letters of recommendation and possibly oral interviews.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In most cases, however, especially for the doctorate, the candidate is required to submit a research plan, and one faculty member must agree to serve as supervisor before the candidate can be admitted into the program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] There are two types of post-graduate programs: *lato sensu* (specialization and MBAs) and *stricto sensu* (professional master's, master's, and doctorate).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Specializations or MBAs are courses that include taking a minimum number of graduate classes (minimum of 360 hours) but with no need to do research nor defend a thesis, only to present final work showing knowledge acquired.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] It is a professional level where theory and practice are focused broadly.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Professional master's or master's degrees usually take one to two years of full-time study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The emphasis of the thesis must be in adding some value to knowledge, but not necessarily in being original.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees normally take four additional years of full-time study to complete.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Requirements for obtaining a doctor's degree include taking additional advanced courses, passing an oral qualifying exam, and submitting a longer doctoral dissertation which must represent a significant original contribution to knowledge in the field to which the dissertation topic is related.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] That contrasts with master's thesis, which, in addition to being usually shorter than doctoral dissertations, are not required to include creation of new knowledge or revision/reinterpretation of older views/theories.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The doctoral dissertation is examined in a final oral exam before a panel of at least two members (in the state of São Paulo the preferred number is five, while the other regions prefer three members), usually including one or two external examiners from another university or research institute.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, the system of academic degrees is based in the British model, similar to the U.S. model.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] After completing their "bachillerato" (high school), students can take one of three options.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The first one is called a *profesional* (professional career), which is similar to a bachelor's degree requiring from four to 6 years of study according to the chosen program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The other option is called a *técnico* (technician); this degree consists of two and a half years of study and prepares the student for technical or mechanical labors.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Finally, the third option is called a *tecnólogo* (equivalent to associate degree) and consists of three years of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] After this, students, now called *profesional* (professionals), *técnicos* (technicians) or *tecnólogos* (associates), can opt for higher degrees.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Formal education after the bachelor's degree leads to the master's degree with the title of *maestro* and doctorate degrees, known as *doctorado* (doctorate).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The master's degree normally takes two years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Students also can take a specialization course, *especialización*, equivalent to a graduate certificate degree, after their bachelor's degree.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These programs, like in the U.S., are very popular, because it requires only one to two years of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, similar to the U.S. system, the students may not go directly to the *doctorado* without having the "master" degree first.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] After completing *enseñanza media* (high school), students receive a *Licenciatura de Enseñanza Media* (high school diploma), which is a requirement for higher education.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Higher-education programs that provide a professional title but not an academic degree are referred to as *carreras técnicas*, which are similar in duration and scope to associate degree programs.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] These are often granted by educational institutions of the type *instituto profesional* (IP) or *centro de formación técnica* (CFT).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Academic degrees in Venezuela start with the *Certificado de Educación Básica* (Certificate of Basic Education), awarded upon completing the 9th grade.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The next degree is earned upon completing the 11th grade and confers the title of *Bachiller en Ciencias* (High School Graduate of Science), *Bachiller en Humanidades* (High School Graduate of Humanities) or *Técnico en Ciencias* (Science Technician).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Titles at the higher-education level usually depend on the institution handing them out.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Technical schools award the student with the title of *Técnico Superior Universitario* (university higher technician, to distinguish from science technician).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Universities award the student with the title of *ingeniero* (engineer) or with the title *licenciado* (licentiate) after completing a five-year program.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The ingeniero degree requires more physics than the licenciado degree, but both take five years.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Some higher-education institutions may award *diplomados* (diploma), but the time necessary to obtain one varies.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Medical doctors are awarded the title "Médico Cirujano" after completing a 6-year course of study.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate education in Venezuela follows the conventions of the United States (being named "master's" and "doctorate" after the programs there).
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The nature of academic degrees from ecclesiastical institutions of education is outlined in the apostolic constitution *Sapientia Christiana*.
[src:university/academic-degree-p04] The core of degrees granted by pontifical universities consists of three levels: the first is the baccalaureate; the second is the licentiate; the third is the doctorate.
[src:university/university] A **university** (from Latin *universitas* 'a whole') is an institution of tertiary education and research which awards academic degrees in several academic disciplines.
[src:university/university] *University* is derived from the Latin phrase *universitas magistrorum et scholarium*, which roughly means "community of teachers and scholars".
[src:university/university] Universities typically offer both undergraduate and postgraduate programs.
[src:university/university] The first universities were developed in Europe from schools that had been maintained by the Church for the purpose of educating priests.
[src:university/university] The original Latin word *universitas* refers in general to "a number of persons associated into one body, a society, company, community, guild, corporation, etc".
[src:university/university] As urban town life and medieval guilds developed, specialized associations of students and teachers with collective legal rights (these rights were usually guaranteed by charters issued by princes, prelates, or their towns) became denominated by this general term.
[src:university/university] Like other guilds, they were self-regulating and determined the qualifications of their members.
[src:university/university] In modern usage, the word has come to mean "an institution of higher education offering tuition in mainly non-vocational subjects and typically having the power to confer degrees".
[src:university/university] The earlier emphasis on its corporate organization is no longer the primary feature by which a modern university is recognized.
[src:university/university] The original Latin word referred to degree-awarding institutions of learning in Western and Central Europe, where this form of legal organisation was prevalent and from where the institution spread around the world.
[src:university/university] An important idea in the definition of a university is the notion of academic freedom.
[src:university/university] The first documentary evidence of this comes from early in the life of the University of Bologna, which adopted an academic charter, the *Constitutio Habita*, in 1155 or 1158, which guaranteed the right of a traveling scholar to unhindered passage in the interests of education.
[src:university/university] Today, this is claimed as the origin of "academic freedom".
[src:university/university] On 18 September 1988, 430 university rectors signed the *Magna Charta Universitatum*, marking the 900th anniversary of Bologna's foundation.
[src:university/university] The School of Alexandria was established during the 2nd century A.D.
[src:university/university] Apart from subjects like theology, Christian philosophy and the Bible; science, mathematics and Greek and Roman literature, logic and the arts were also taught.
[src:university/university] The question-and-answer method of commentary began there, and blind students at the school were using wood-carving techniques to read and write.
[src:university/university] The first figures of the Church in Egypt were scholars rather than bishops, directors of the Catechetical School of Alexandria: Clement (160–215) and Origen (185–251).
[src:university/university] Nalanda mahavihara was established by emperor Kumaragupta I of the Gupta Empire around 427 CE, became a major Buddhist learning hub, attracting scholars like Xuanzang.
[src:university/university] It was destroyed in 1202 CE by Bakhtiyar Khilji.
[src:university/university] The characterization of Nalanda as a "university" in the modern sense has been challenged by scholars.
[src:university/university] They argue that while it was undoubtedly a major center of learning, comparing it directly to a modern university is historically imprecise.
[src:university/university] During and after the mission of St Augustine to England, cathedral schools were established as the new dioceses were themselves created (Canterbury 597, Rochester 604, York 627, for example).
[src:university/university] Cathedral schools arose in major cities such as Chartres, Orleans, Paris, Laon, Reims or Rouen in France and Utrecht, Liege, Cologne, Metz, Speyer, Würzburg, Bamberg, Magdeburg, Hildesheim or Freising in Germany.
[src:university/university] Speyer was renowned for supplying the Holy Roman Empire with diplomats.
[src:university/university] The court of Henry I of England, was tied to the cathedral school of Laon.
[src:university/university] Centers of learning were found in seventh-century Spain, both at major monasteries and at episcopal centers.
[src:university/university] Students at the monastery of Saints Cosmas and Damian, at Agali near Toledo, learned such scientific subjects as medicine and the rudiments of astronomy.
[src:university/university] In the heyday of the monastic schools in the 9th and 10th centuries, the teachings of important scholars such as Alcuin, Hrabanus Maurus, Heiric of Auxerre and Notker Balbulus raised the prestige of their abbeys and attracted pupils from afar to attend their courses.
[src:university/university] An early institution is the Madrasa of Harran, founded in the late 8th century.
[src:university/university] Scholars occasionally call the University of al-Qarawiyyin (name given in 1963), founded as a mosque by Fatima al-Fihri in 859 CE, a university, although Jacques Verger writes that this is done out of scholarly convenience.
[src:university/university] Several scholars consider that al-Qarawiyyin was founded and run as a madrasa until after World War II.
[src:university/university] They date the transformation of the madrasa of al-Qarawiyyin into a university to its modern reorganization in 1963.
[src:university/university] In the wake of these reforms, al-Qarawiyyin was officially renamed "University of Al Quaraouiyine" two years later.
[src:university/university] Some scholars, including George Makdisi, have argued that early medieval universities were influenced by the madrasas in Al-Andalus, the Emirate of Sicily, and the Middle East during the Crusades.
[src:university/university] Norman Daniel, however, views this argument as overstated.
[src:university/university] Universities and madrasas differed in several major respects.
[src:university/university] Although there are antecedents, the modern university is generally regarded as a formal institution that has its origin in the Medieval Christian tradition.
[src:university/university] European higher education took place for hundreds of years in cathedral schools or monastic schools (*scholae monasticae*), in which monks and nuns taught classes; evidence of these immediate forerunners of the later university at many places dates back to the 6th century.
[src:university/university] In Europe, young men proceeded to university when they had completed their study of the trivium – the preparatory arts of grammar, rhetoric and dialectic or logic–and the quadrivium: arithmetic, geometry, music, and astronomy.
[src:university/university] The earliest universities were developed under the aegis of the Latin Church by papal bull as *studia generalia* and perhaps from cathedral schools.
[src:university/university] It is possible, however, that the development of cathedral schools into universities was quite rare, with the University of Paris being an exception.
[src:university/university] Later they were also founded by kings - but with prior papal approval.
[src:university/university] (University of Naples Federico II, Charles University in Prague, Jagiellonian University in Kraków) or municipal administrations (University of Cologne, University of Erfurt).
[src:university/university] Most of the early universities of the high medieval period were founded from pre-existing schools, usually when these schools were deemed to have become primarily sites of higher education.
[src:university/university] Many historians state that universities and cathedral schools were a continuation of the interest in learning promoted by monasteries.
[src:university/university] Pope Gregory VII was crucial in promoting and regulating the concept of modern university, as his 1079 Papal Decree ordered the regulated establishment of cathedral schools that transformed themselves into the first European universities.
[src:university/university] The first universities in Europe with a form of corporate/guild structure were the University of Bologna (c.
[src:university/university] 1208–1210, later associated with the Sorbonne), and the University of Oxford (c.
[src:university/university] The University of Bologna began as a law school teaching the *ius gentium* or Roman law of peoples which was in demand across Europe for those defending the right of incipient nations against empire and church.
[src:university/university] The University of Bologna, or *Alma Mater Studiorum*, is widely recognized as the oldest university that is independent of any direct authority, such as kings, emperors, or religious organizations.
[src:university/university] Bologna's claim to being the oldest university is based on its unique characteristics, such as its autonomy and its ability to grant degrees.
[src:university/university] The conventional date for the start of teaching at Bologna of 1088, or 1087 according to some, records when Irnerius commenced teaching Emperor Justinian's 6th-century codification of Roman law, the *Corpus Iuris Civilis*, recently discovered at Pisa.
[src:university/university] Lay students arrived in the city from many lands entering into a contract to gain this knowledge, eventually organising themselves into *Nationes*, divided between that of the Cismontanes and that of the Ultramontanes.
[src:university/university] The students "had all the power ... and dominated the masters".
[src:university/university] All over Europe, rulers and city governments began to create universities to satisfy a European thirst for knowledge, and the belief that society would benefit from the scholarly expertise generated from these institutions.
[src:university/university] Princes and leaders of city governments perceived the potential benefits of having a scholarly expertise developed with the ability to address difficult problems and achieve desired ends.
[src:university/university] The emergence of humanism was essential to this understanding of the possible utility of universities as well as the revival of interest in knowledge gained from ancient Greek texts.
[src:university/university] The recovery of Aristotle's works – more than 3000 pages of it would eventually be translated – fuelled a spirit of inquiry into natural processes that had already begun to emerge in the 12th century.
[src:university/university] Some scholars believe that these works represented one of the most important document discoveries in Western intellectual history.
[src:university/university] The efforts of this "scholasticism" were focused on applying Aristotelian logic and thoughts about natural processes to biblical passages and attempting to prove the viability of those passages through reason.
[src:university/university] This became the primary mission of lecturers, and the expectation of students.
[src:university/university] The university culture developed differently in northern Europe than it did in the south, although the northern (primarily Germany, France and Great Britain) and southern universities (primarily Italy) did have many elements in common.
[src:university/university] Latin was the language of the university, used for all texts, lectures, disputations and examinations.
[src:university/university] Professors lectured on the books of Aristotle for logic, natural philosophy, and metaphysics; while Hippocrates, Galen, and Avicenna were used for medicine.
[src:university/university] Outside of these commonalities, great differences separated north and south, primarily in subject matter.
[src:university/university] Italian universities focused on law and medicine, while the northern universities focused on the arts and theology.
[src:university/university] The quality of instruction in the different areas of study varied, depending on the university's focus.
[src:university/university] This led scholars to travel north or south based on their interests and means.
[src:university/university] The universities also awarded different types of degrees.
[src:university/university] English, French and German universities usually awarded bachelor's degrees, with the exception of degrees in theology, for which the doctorate was more common.
[src:university/university] Italian universities awarded primarily doctorates.
[src:university/university] The distinction can be attributed to the intent of the degree holder after graduation – in the north the focus tended to be on acquiring teaching positions, while in the south students often went on to professional positions.
[src:university/university] The structure of northern universities tended to be modeled after the system of faculty governance developed at the University of Paris.
[src:university/university] Southern universities tended to be patterned after the student-controlled model begun at the University of Bologna.
[src:university/university] During the Early Modern period (approximately late 15th century to 1800), the universities of Europe would see a tremendous amount of growth, productivity and innovative research.
[src:university/university] At the end of the Middle Ages, about 400 years after the first European university was founded, there were 29 universities spread throughout Europe.
[src:university/university] In the 15th century, 28 new ones were created, with another 18 added between 1500 and 1625.
[src:university/university] This number does not include the numerous universities that disappeared, or institutions that merged with other universities during this time.
[src:university/university] The identification of a university was not necessarily obvious during the early modern period, as the term is applied to a burgeoning number of institutions.
[src:university/university] In fact, the term "university" was not always used to designate a higher education institution.
[src:university/university] In Mediterranean countries, the term *studium generale* was still often used, while "Academy" was common in Northern European countries.
[src:university/university] The propagation of universities was not necessarily a steady progression, as the 17th century was rife with events that adversely affected university expansion.
[src:university/university] Many wars, and especially the Thirty Years' War, disrupted the university landscape throughout Europe at different times.
[src:university/university] War, plague, famine, regicide, and changes in religious power and structure often adversely affected the societies that provided support for universities.
[src:university/university] Internal strife within the universities themselves, such as student brawling and absentee professors, acted to destabilize these institutions as well.
[src:university/university] Universities were also reluctant to give up older curricula, and the continued reliance on the works of Aristotle defied contemporary advancements in science and the arts.
[src:university/university] This era was also affected by the rise of the nation-state.
[src:university/university] As universities increasingly came under state control, or formed under the auspices of the state, the faculty governance model (begun by the University of Paris) became more and more prominent.
[src:university/university] Although the older student-controlled universities still existed, they slowly started to move toward this structural organization.
[src:university/university] Control of universities still tended to be independent, although university leadership was increasingly appointed by the state.
[src:university/university] Although the structural model provided by the University of Paris, where student members are controlled by faculty "masters", provided a standard for universities, the application of this model took at least three different forms.
[src:university/university] There were universities that had a system of faculties whose teaching addressed a very specific curriculum; this model tended to train specialists.
[src:university/university] There was a collegiate or tutorial model based on the system at University of Oxford where teaching and organization was decentralized and knowledge was more of a generalist nature.
[src:university/university] There were also universities that combined these models, using the collegiate model but having a centralized organization.
[src:university/university] Early Modern universities initially continued the curriculum and research of the Middle Ages: natural philosophy, logic, medicine, theology, mathematics, astronomy, astrology, law, grammar and rhetoric.
[src:university/university] Aristotle was prevalent throughout the curriculum, while medicine also depended on Galen and Arabic scholarship.
[src:university/university] The importance of humanism for changing this state-of-affairs cannot be underestimated.
[src:university/university] Once humanist professors joined the university faculty, they began to transform the study of grammar and rhetoric through the studia humanitatis.
[src:university/university] Humanist professors focused on the ability of students to write and speak with distinction, to translate and interpret classical texts, and to live honorable lives.
[src:university/university] Other scholars within the university were affected by the humanist approaches to learning and their linguistic expertise in relation to ancient texts, as well as the ideology that advocated the ultimate importance of those texts.
[src:university/university] Professors of medicine such as Niccolò Leoniceno, Thomas Linacre and William Cop were often trained in and taught from a humanist perspective as well as translated important ancient medical texts.
[src:university/university] The critical mindset imparted by humanism was imperative for changes in universities and scholarship.
[src:university/university] For instance, Andreas Vesalius was educated in a humanist fashion before producing a translation of Galen, whose ideas he verified through his own dissections.
[src:university/university] In law, Andreas Alciatus infused the *Corpus Juris* with a humanist perspective, while Jacques Cujas humanist writings were paramount to his reputation as a jurist.
[src:university/university] Philipp Melanchthon cited the works of Erasmus as a highly influential guide for connecting theology back to original texts, which was important for the reform at Protestant universities.
[src:university/university] Galileo Galilei, who taught at the Universities of Pisa and Padua, and Martin Luther, who taught at the University of Wittenberg (as did Melanchthon), also had humanist training.
[src:university/university] The task of the humanists was to slowly permeate the university; to increase the humanist presence in professorships and chairs, syllabi and textbooks so that published works would demonstrate the humanistic ideal of science and scholarship.
[src:university/university] Although the initial focus of the humanist scholars in the university was the discovery, exposition and insertion of ancient texts and languages into the university, and the ideas of those texts into society generally, their influence was ultimately quite progressive.
[src:university/university] The emergence of classical texts brought new ideas and led to a more creative university climate (as the notable list of scholars above attests to).
[src:university/university] A focus on knowledge coming from self, from the human, has a direct implication for new forms of scholarship and instruction, and was the foundation for what is commonly known as the humanities.
[src:university/university] This disposition toward knowledge manifested in not simply the translation and propagation of ancient texts, but also their adaptation and expansion.
[src:university/university] For instance, Vesalius was imperative for advocating the use of Galen, but he also invigorated this text with experimentation, disagreements and further research.
[src:university/university] The propagation of these texts, especially within the universities, was greatly aided by the emergence of the printing press and the beginning of the use of the vernacular, which allowed for the printing of relatively large texts at reasonable prices.
[src:university/university] Examining the influence of humanism on scholars in medicine, mathematics, astronomy and physics may suggest that humanism and universities were a strong impetus for the scientific revolution.
[src:university/university] Although the connection between humanism and the scientific discovery may very well have begun within the confines of the university, the connection has been commonly perceived as having been severed by the changing nature of science during the Scientific Revolution.
[src:university/university] Westfall have argued that the overt traditionalism of universities inhibited attempts to re-conceptualize nature and knowledge and caused an indelible tension between universities and scientists.
[src:university/university] This resistance to changes in science may have been a significant factor in driving many scientists away from the university and toward private benefactors, usually in princely courts, and associations with newly forming scientific societies.
[src:university/university] Other historians find incongruity in the proposition that the very place where the vast number of the scholars that influenced the scientific revolution received their education should also be the place that inhibits their research and the advancement of science.
[src:university/university] In fact, more than 80% of the European scientists between 1450 and 1650 included in the Dictionary of Scientific Biography were university trained, of which approximately 45% held university posts.
[src:university/university] It was the case that the academic foundations remaining from the Middle Ages were stable, and they did provide for an environment that fostered considerable growth and development.
[src:university/university] There was considerable reluctance on the part of universities to relinquish the symmetry and comprehensiveness provided by the Aristotelian system, which was effective as a coherent system for understanding and interpreting the world.
[src:university/university] However, university professors still have some autonomy, at least in the sciences, to choose epistemological foundations and methods.
[src:university/university] For instance, Melanchthon and his disciples at University of Wittenberg were instrumental for integrating Copernican mathematical constructs into astronomical debate and instruction.
[src:university/university] Another example was the short-lived but fairly rapid adoption of Cartesian epistemology and methodology in European universities, and the debates surrounding that adoption, which led to more mechanistic approaches to scientific problems as well as demonstrated an openness to change.
[src:university/university] There are many examples which belie the commonly perceived intransigence of universities.
[src:university/university] Although universities may have been slow to accept new sciences and methodologies as they emerged, when they did accept new ideas it helped to convey legitimacy and respectability, and supported the scientific changes through providing a stable environment for instruction and material resources.
[src:university/university] Regardless of the way the tension between universities, individual scientists, and the scientific revolution itself is perceived, there was a discernible impact on the way that university education was constructed.
[src:university/university] Aristotelian epistemology provided a coherent framework not simply for knowledge and knowledge construction, but also for the training of scholars within the higher education setting.
[src:university/university] The creation of new scientific constructs during the scientific revolution, and the epistemological challenges that were inherent within this creation, initiated the idea of both the autonomy of science and the hierarchy of the disciplines.
[src:university/university] Instead of entering higher education to become a "general scholar" immersed in becoming proficient in the entire curriculum, there emerged a type of scholar that put science first and viewed it as a vocation in itself.
[src:university/university] The divergence between those focused on science and those still entrenched in the idea of a general scholar exacerbated the epistemological tensions that were already beginning to emerge.
[src:university/university] The epistemological tensions between scientists and universities were also heightened by the economic realities of research during this time, as individual scientists, associations and universities were vying for limited resources.
[src:university/university] There was also competition from the formation of new colleges funded by private benefactors and designed to provide free education to the public, or established by local governments to provide a knowledge-hungry populace with an alternative to traditional universities.
[src:university/university] Even when universities supported new scientific endeavors, and the university provided foundational training and authority for the research and conclusions, they could not compete with the resources available through private benefactors.
[src:university/university] By the end of the early modern period, the structure and orientation of higher education had changed in ways that are eminently recognizable for the modern context.
[src:university/university] Aristotle was no longer a force providing the epistemological and methodological focus for universities and a more mechanistic orientation was emerging.
[src:university/university] The hierarchical place of theological knowledge had for the most part been displaced and the humanities had become a fixture, and a new openness was beginning to take hold in the construction and dissemination of knowledge that were to become imperative for the formation of the modern state.
[src:university/university] Modern universities constitute a guild or quasi-guild system.
[src:university/university] By the 18th century, universities published their own research journals and by the 19th century, the German and the French university models had arisen.
[src:university/university] The German, or Humboldtian model, was conceived by Wilhelm von Humboldt and based on Friedrich Schleiermacher's liberal ideas pertaining to the importance of freedom, seminars, and laboratories in universities.
[src:university/university] The French university model involved strict discipline and control over every aspect of the university.
[src:university/university] Until the 19th century, religion played a significant role in university curriculum; however, the role of religion in research universities decreased during that century.
[src:university/university] By the end of the 19th century, the German university model had spread around the world.
[src:university/university] Universities concentrated on science in the 19th and 20th centuries and became increasingly accessible to the masses.
[src:university/university] In the United States, the Johns Hopkins University was the first to adopt the (German) research university model and pioneered the adoption of that model by most American universities.
[src:university/university] In Scotland, the Andersonian Institute, founded in the late 18th century with a similar emphasis, became the University of Strathclyde in the 1960s as the first new university in Scotland since Edinburgh in the 16th century.
[src:university/university] The British also established universities worldwide, and higher education became available to the masses not only in Europe.
[src:university/university] In the early 21st century, concerns were raised over the increasing managerialisation and standardisation of universities worldwide.
[src:university/university] Neo-liberal management models have in this sense been critiqued for creating "corporate universities (where) power is transferred from faculty to managers, economic justifications dominate, and the familiar 'bottom line' eclipses pedagogical or intellectual concerns".
[src:university/university] Academics' understanding of time, pedagogical pleasure, vocation, and collegiality have been cited as possible ways of alleviating such problems.
[src:university/university] A national university is generally a university created or run by a national state but at the same time represents a state autonomic institution which functions as a completely independent body inside of the same state.
[src:university/university] In the years leading up to the Easter Rising, and in no small part a result of the Gaelic Romantic revivalists, the NUI collected a large amount of information on the Irish language and Irish culture.
[src:university/university] Reforms in Argentina were the result of the University Revolution of 1918 and its posterior reforms by incorporating values that sought for a more equal and laic higher education system.
[src:university/university] Universities created by bilateral or multilateral treaties between states are intergovernmental.
[src:university/university] An example is the Academy of European Law, which offers training in European law to lawyers, judges, barristers, solicitors, in-house counsel and academics.
[src:university/university] The European University Institute, a post-graduate university specialized in the social sciences, is officially an intergovernmental organization, set up by the member states of the European Union.
[src:university/university] Although each institution is organized differently, nearly all universities have a board of trustees; a president, chancellor, or rector; at least one vice president, vice-chancellor, or vice-rector; and deans of various divisions.
[src:university/university] Universities are generally divided into a number of academic departments, schools or faculties.
[src:university/university] They review financial requests and budget proposals and then allocate funds for each university in the system.
[src:university/university] They also approve new programs of instruction and cancel or make changes in existing programs.
[src:university/university] In addition, they plan for the further coordinated growth and development of the various institutions of higher education in the state or country.
[src:university/university] Many universities in the world have a considerable degree of financial, research and pedagogical autonomy.
[src:university/university] Private universities are privately funded and generally have broader independence from state policies.
[src:university/university] The funding and organization of universities varies widely between different countries around the world.
[src:university/university] In some countries universities are predominantly funded by the state, while in others funding may come from donors or from fees which students attending the university must pay.
[src:university/university] In some countries the vast majority of students attend university in their local town, while in other countries universities attract students from all over the world, and may provide university accommodation for their students.
[src:university/university] The definition of a university varies widely, even within some countries.
[src:university/university] Where there is clarification, it is usually set by a government agency.
[src:university/university] In Australia, the Tertiary Education Quality and Standards Agency (TEQSA) is Australia's independent national regulator of the higher education sector.
[src:university/university] Students rights within university are also protected by the Education Services for Overseas Students Act (ESOS).
[src:university/university] In the United States there is no nationally standardized definition for the term *university*, although the term has traditionally been used to designate research institutions and was once reserved for doctorate-granting research institutions.
[src:university/university] Some states, such as Massachusetts, will only grant a school "university status" if it grants at least two doctoral degrees.
[src:university/university] In the United Kingdom, the Privy Council is responsible for approving the use of the word *university* in the name of an institution, under the terms of the Further and Higher Education Act 1992.
[src:university/university] Institutions that are 'deemed-to-be-university' enjoy the academic status and the privileges of a university.
[src:university/university] Through this provision many schools that are commercial in nature and have been established just to exploit the demand for higher education have sprung up.
[src:university/university] In Canada, *college* generally refers to a two-year, non-degree-granting institution, while *university* connotes a four-year, degree-granting institution.
[src:university/university] In Germany, universities are institutions of higher education which have the power to confer bachelor, master and PhD degrees.
[src:university/university] They are explicitly recognised as such by law and cannot be founded without government approval.
[src:university/university] The term Universität (i.e. the German term for university) is protected by law and any use without official approval is a criminal offense.
[src:university/university] Most of them are public institutions, though a few private universities exist.
[src:university/university] Such universities are always research universities.
[src:university/university] Apart from these universities, Germany has other institutions of higher education (Hochschule, *Fachhochschule*).
[src:university/university] *Fachhochschule* means a higher education institution which is similar to the former polytechnics in the British education system, the English term used for these German institutions is usually 'university of applied sciences'.
[src:university/university] They can confer master's degrees but no PhDs.
[src:university/university] They are similar to the model of teaching universities with less research and the research undertaken being highly practical.
[src:university/university] Hochschule can refer to various kinds of institutions, often specialised in a certain field (e.g. music, fine arts, business).
[src:university/university] They might or might not have the power to award PhD degrees, depending on the respective government legislation.
[src:university/university] If they award PhD degrees, their rank is considered equivalent to that of universities proper (Universität), if not, their rank is equivalent to universities of applied sciences.
[src:university/university] Colloquially, the term *university* may be used to describe a phase in one's life: "When I was at university..." (in the United States and Ireland, *college* is often used instead: "When I was in college...").
[src:university/university] In Ireland, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, the United Kingdom, Nigeria, the Netherlands, Spain and the German-speaking countries, *university* is often contracted to *uni*.
[src:university/university] In Ghana, New Zealand, Bangladesh and in South Africa it is sometimes called "varsity" (although this has become uncommon in New Zealand in recent years).
[src:university/university] "Varsity" was also common usage in the UK in the 19th century.
[src:university/university] In many countries, students are required to pay tuition fees.
[src:university/university] Many students look to get 'student grants' to cover the cost of university.
[src:university/university] In 2016, the average outstanding student loan balance per borrower in the United States was US$30,000.
[src:university/university] In many U.S. states, costs are anticipated to rise for students as a result of decreased state funding given to public universities.
[src:university/university] Many universities in the United States offer students the opportunity to apply for financial scholarships to help pay for tuition based on academic achievement.
[src:university/university] There are several major exceptions on tuition fees.
[src:university/university] In many European countries, it is possible to study without tuition fees.
[src:university/university] Public universities in Nordic countries were entirely without tuition fees until around 2005.
[src:university/university] Denmark, Sweden and Finland then moved to put in place tuition fees for foreign students.
[src:university/university] Citizens of EU and EEA member states and citizens from Switzerland remain exempted from tuition fees, and the amounts of public grants granted to promising foreign students were increased to offset some of the impact.
[src:university/university] The situation in Germany is similar; public universities usually do not charge tuition fees apart from a small administrative fee.
[src:university/university] For degrees of a postgraduate professional level sometimes tuition fees are levied.
[src:university/university] Private universities, however, almost always charge tuition fees.
